<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Opposes Military Solution to Kashmir Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Visiting French Chief of
Defense Staff General Jean Pierre Kelche said here on Monday that
France believed there could be no military solution to the Kashmir
issue and the only way forward was through a dialogue.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference following his meeting with Indian Defense
Minister George Fernandes, the French general also described the
Kashmir issue as a bilateral matter between India and Pakistan
which France does not want to interfere with.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that India and France, after several rounds
of strategic dialogue, were poised to develop a "global
partnership" and a united strategy against international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
While France was giving top priority to building military and
strategic cooperation with India, it did not want Pakistan to be
isolated, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation between France and India and France and Pakistan
are at different levels," said the French general.
</P>
<P>
Denying that his trip had been prompted by defense deals, he
also asserted that many conventional weapons and military
technologies France could offer to India are advanced and viable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
