<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Lankan Troops Retreat to Defend Jaffna Peninsula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan troops had retreated
tactically from a strategic military base to defend the northern
Jaffna peninsula, Army Commander Srilal Weerasooriya said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Holding of the peninsula is our priority," Weerasooriya told a
news conference here Monday evening, adding that the retreat from
the Elephant Pass last Saturday was "in the larger interest of
safeguarding the Jaffna peninsula."
</P>
<P>
The Elephant Pass is a narrow causeway linking the Jaffna
peninsula with the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
Jaffna is the center of Tamil culture and was the rebel capital
until December 1995 when government troops captured the city and
dealt a big blow to the morale of the separatist Liberation Tigers
of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the LTTE rebels said on Monday they had overrun
another government camp in northern Sri Lanka after their capture
of the Elephant Pass.
</P>
<P>
The rebels said they had smashed through government defense
lines at Soranpattu, just north of the strategic Elephant Pass.
</P>
<P>
However, Weerasooriya denied the rebel claim.
</P>
<P>
He also rejected the LTTE claim that more than 1,000 soldiers
had been killed in the weekend fighting, saying eight officers and
80 soldiers had been killed.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministry earlier said 625 troops were wounded.
</P>
<P>
Military officials said that troops were consolidating their
positions in new areas north of the Elephant Pass to ward off
fresh attacks to Jaffna by the LTTE rebels.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels, fighting since 1983 for a separate state for
minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east, also said Monday
they had seized a huge supply of weapons, ammunition and military
vehicles from the base at the Elephant Pass.
</P>
<P>
The rebels said 35 of their fighters had died in the fighting
over the weekend, while the government put the number of
separatists killed at around 200.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's main opposition United National Party (UNP) has
called for an emergency session of parliament to discuss the rebel
onslaught.
</P>
<P>
The party said it wrote to parliamentary speaker K.B. Ratnayake
to summon the assembly ahead of the scheduled May 9 session.
</P>
<P>
The clashes in the north came amid moves by Norway to bring the
Tamil Tigers and the Sri Lankan government to the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the victory at the Elephant Pass gave the rebels
stronger bargaining power if they were to open talks with the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
