<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Students Across Iran Protest Conservative Crackdown  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Iranian students in various cities
on Tuesday took to the streets to "defend the freedom of speech" as
the powerful conservatives have intensified crackdown on the
reformists and their publications.
</P>
<P>
The official Islamic Republic News Agency reported that
university students staged protesting rallies and sit-ins in
Tehran, Bandar Abbas of southeastern Hormozgan province, Yazd of
central Yazd province, Kashan of central Isfahan province, Shiraz
of southern Fars province and Hamadan of the western Hamadan
province.
</P>
<P>
The students condemned the closure of 13 reformist publications
and the state television's screening of selective parts of a
controversial conference on Iran in German capital of Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Students from Khajeh Nassir Tussi Technical University in Tehran
held a demonstration calling on President Mohammad Khatami to pay
more attention to the attempts underway to obstruct the reform
process in the country.
</P>
<P>
Elected Majlis (parliament) member Ali Akbar Musavi Khoeini
delivered a speech to the students, who issued a five-point
resolution in support of the reformist press and freedom of the
press.
</P>
<P>
The agency did not say how many people participated in the
demonstrations in the major cities while witnesses put the number
in Tehran at around 1,000.
</P>
<P>
Students also reportedly rallied at Tehran University overnight
after the conservative judiciary ordered the closure of 13
reformist dailies and periodicals, including two most popular
dailies--Fath (Conquer) and Asr-e Azadegan (Times of the Freed).
</P>
<P>
The closure of another prominent reformist daily Sobh-e Emrouz
(This Morning) was revoked later Monday night as its managing
director, Saeed Hajjarian, is still hospitalized after being shot
in an assassination attempt on March 12.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives, who control most of the country's powers,
suffered serious setbacks in elections in the past two years. They
seemed determined to revenge their humiliating defeat in the
February parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
The conservative watchdog Guardians Council announced on Tuesday
that it found errors in vote-recounting in Tehran, where the
reformists won 29 of 30 seats in the elections. It has already
deprived nine elected reformists of their eligibility.
</P>
<P>
The reformists were expected to take over the Majlis on May 28,
but the new Majlis can officially start its work only after a
minimum of 190 parliamentarians were confirmed by the Guardians
Council.
</P>
<P>
If the election results in Tehran are nullified, the new Majlis
must wait until the result of the run-off.
</P>
<P>
The Special Court for Clergy, also dominated by the
conservatives, issued an arrest warrant against the reformist
cleric Hassan Yussefi Eshkevari for his participation in a
conference on Iran in Berlin, Germany.
</P>
<P>
Eshkevari was charged with "actions against national security,
propaganda against the system, insult to and rejection of the
absolute sanctities of Islam, and behavior not befitting the
clergy."
</P>
<P>
Eshkevari, a supporter of Khatami's reform policies, was among a
group of reformist invited to the controversial Berlin conference
titled "Iran After February Elections."
</P>
<P>
Hard-liners have organized rallies throughout the country over
the past few days to denounce the Berlin conference and increase
pressure on the reformists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
