<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF: Only Strong Political Will Can Roll Back Malaria in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF)on Tuesday appealed to African heads of
state to provide the leadership and resources to control malaria
throughout Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Malaria contributes significantly to the high death rates of
children and women recorded in Africa, even through we now have
the means to make major inroads against the disease," UNICEF
Executive Director Carol Bellamy said.
</P>
<P>
"We now have effective, affordable interventions to prevent
and cure malaria," she said. "But we cannot deploy the means if
the political will is lacking."
</P>
<P>
 The UNICEF chief made the appeal in Nigeria's administrative
capital, Abuja, where African government leaders are attending the
world's first-ever summit on Malaria.
</P>
<P>
 The summit is considering how to speed action to alleviate
the poverty and human suffering caused by the disease.
</P>
<P>
 Attending heads of state are expected to endorse the goal of
the global Roll Back Malaria (RBM) movement to reduce malaria
deaths by half by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
 UNICEF is currently supporting malaria control programs in 30
countries in Africa to reduce the toll of the disease on young
children and pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
 "we recognized that there are tremendous pressure on the
Governments meeting here," said Bellamy.
</P>
<P>
"But now we have a clear-cut opportunity. Together we can
prove that, with local participation and focused political will at
all levels, leadership on behalf of children is the most effective
key to progress in the new millennium," she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Premier-designate Amato Nominates New Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Italian Premier-designate Giuliano
Amato Tuesday nominated 24 ministers who should form the 58th post-
war Italian government after the approval of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Lamberto Dini remains as foreign minister, Sergio Mattarella as
minister of defense, treasury minister is former Finance Minister
Vicenzo Visco, Ottaviano Del Turco will be the finance minister,
former Foreign Trade Minister Piero Fassino moved to the ministry
of justice, Ministry of Foreign Trade will be canceled in Amato
government.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency Ansa, lowering fiscal pressure
for both individuals and firms and taking a tough line on law and
order issues were two key planks in Amato government's program.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, one of Amato's main objectives is said to be that of
reducing the number of undersecretaries, which numbered 56 in
outgoing Premier Massimo D'Alema's first government, formed in
October 1998,rising to 66 in his second, put together at Christmas
time.
</P>
<P>
Italian President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, who asked Amato to try
and form a new government on Friday evening, has stressed that he
would like to see a slim-line administration.
</P>
<P>
If he can muster up enough support in parliament and pass a
confidence vote in both houses, he will become the head of Italy's
58th post-war government, which could be sworn-in as early as next
week.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing Premier D'Alema quit his job last Wednesday after the
center-left suffered a humiliating defeat in Sunday's regional
elections, emerging with seven regions to the center-right's eight
and polling about 45 percent of the vote against the opposition's
51 percent.
</P>
<P>
Amato, 61, is a former Socialist who served as premier from
1992-93 and was a top aid to the late disgraced Socialist leader
Bettino Craxi.
</P>
<P>
His reputation was virtually unscathed by the corruption
scandals that toppled his political master and destroyed his party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
