<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian FM Tells France Syria's Analysis of Israeli Pullout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Syrian Foreign Minister
Faruk Shareh Tuesday told his French counterpart Hubert Vedrine
Syria's analysis concerning the pullout of Israel from southern
Lebanon and the consequences it would result in.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said
that during his talks with Vedrine, Shareh also ``presented for a
long time the Syrian position concerning the Syria-Israeli part of
the peace talks as well as the reasons in his eyes for the failure
of the summit in Geneva (between Syrian President Hafez Assad and
U.S. President Bill Clinton).''
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman did not provide further details.
</P>
<P>
Shareh arrived here Tuesday afternoon on a mission representing
Syrian President Hafez Assad to inform France on Damascus's
position on the forthcoming Israeli withdrawal from southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He will be received by French President Jacques Chirac at the
Elysee presidential palace Tuesday evening and will deliver to
Chirac a ``written message'' from Assad to Chirac, said French
officials.
</P>
<P>
France is considering participating in a United Nations
peacekeeping operation in southern Lebanon once Israel pulls out
its troops from there by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
But France insists that such a peacekeeping operation should be
carried out in a safe condition and with the agreement of all
sides involved.
</P>
<P>
France has also repeatedly called on Israel to make such a
pullout within the framework of a peace agreement with both
Lebanon and Syria,rather than doing it unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which has about 30,000 troops deployed in Lebanon, has
accused Israel of trying to fool the world by pretending to pull
out of the 850 square kilometers of territory in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
A senior official of Syria's Baath Socialist Party, Suleyman
Kaddah, said on Monday that Israel was creating a crisis in all
the parts of the peace talks with Arab countries by making a
unilateral pullout from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He also accused Israel of trying to separate Lebanon from Syria
in the talks and said that Damascus and Beirut would work together
to``consolidate the unity of the two parts'' of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between Israel and Syria on a total withdrawal
of Israel from the Golan Heights have been suspended since January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Trial May Be Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The trial of the airliner
bombing over Lockerbie may be postponed after the request for
delay is considered on Thursday at Camp Zeist.
</P>
<P>
The Scottish Crown Office prosecution service said that an
application was presented to the High Court of Justiciary for
postponement of the trial originally scheduled to start on May 3
at Camp Zeist, the former Dutch air force base.
</P>
<P>
"The application has been made in the light of the intimation
by the defense on April 20 of a total of 119 defense witnesses and
of lists of defense productions (objects of evidence)," said the
Scottish Crown Office in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The application will be considered at Camp Zeist, where Libyan
suspects Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Al-Amin Khalifa Fahima will
be tried for the 1988 bombing over the Scottish village of
Lockerbie of a Boeing airliner.
</P>
<P>
Pan Am flight 103 from Frankfurt to New York via London
exploded over Lockerbie, killing all 259 people on board and
another 11 on the ground on December 21, 1988.
</P>
<P>
A three-year investigation concluded to obtain a warrant for
the arrest of the two Libyan suspects, both staff of the Libyan
Arab Airlines in Malta in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Under a deal brokered by the United Nations last year, Libya
handed over the two bombing suspects to stand trial in the
Netherlands under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
The defense witnesses reside in a number of countries including
Malta, Sweden, the United States, Germany as well as Libya.
</P>
<P>
"Given the number, apparent range and geographical location of
defense witnesses, the Prosecutor does not consider that he can
properly proceed to trial without the proper investigation of this
evidence," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
If the postponement was granted, the trial could be delayed by
weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
