<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Allows Elian's Playmates to Visit Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking at a regular briefing, State Department spokesman
James Rubin said visa requests from the four will be dealt with on
an expedited basis once they are received. One adult will be
permitted to accompany each child.
</P>
<P>
The department issued visas almost three weeks ago to Elian's
former kindergarten teacher, a pediatrician and a male cousin,
Rubin noted.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. federal government seized the six-year-old Cuban boy
from the home of his Miami relatives in a predawn raid on Sunday
and reunited Elian and his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, ending a
five-month standoff between the government and Elian's Miami
relatives.
</P>
<P>
Despite the happy reunion of the father and son, some U.S.
politicians were critical of the administration's handling of the
case.
</P>
<P>
Defending the government's handling of the case, President Bill
Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno both indicated that the
authorities used force to remove Elian from his relatives in Miami
after they refused to surrender the boy voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
Elian, his step mother, his father and his half brother have
been staying at a residence at nearby Andrews Air Force Base. They
plan to move shortly to the Wye Plantation, located in a secluded
area on Maryland's Eastern Shore, while awaiting court action over
whether Elian should stay in the U.S. or return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued on November 25 of last year near a shipwreck
in the Atlantic sea off Florida after his mother and 10 others
were drowned when their boat capsized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
