<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Pound Hits Companies' Profitability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The strong pound and higher
interest rates have helped to send the profitability of British
companies declining to a two-year low, a new survey showed.
</P>
<P>
Despite improvements in productivity, the average return on
capital in Britain dropped to 13.14 percent in the last quarter of
1999, the lowest since the third quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest Corporate Health Check by Experian, the
West Midlands was the best-performing region and enjoyed the
highest level of profitability in the UK.
</P>
<P>
However, the information company cautioned that this could be
reversed later in the year in the wake of the break-up of Rover,
the car company in the region.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which analyzed the financial results of the country
's 2000 largest companies, suggested the fall in profitability was
broadly based.
</P>
<P>
Only four of 23 industry sectors studied - building and
construction, alcoholic beverages, food retailing and utilities -
reported an increase in return on capital in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
Over 1999 as a whole, the survey showed eight industry sectors
reported a profitability drop of more than 10 percent, including
IT, pharmaceuticals, transport, and chemicals and plastics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
