<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Voices Deep Concern over United States' NMD System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Sweden on Tuesday
expressed its deep concern over the United States' plans for a
national missile defense (NMD) system, saying such a system could
run counter to efforts to halt proliferation of weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 2000 Review Conference of the Parties to the
Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT) which is
held here from April 24 to May 19, Ms. Anna Lindh, Minister for
Foreign Affairs of Sweden, said proliferation must instead be met
by strengthening the non-proliferation regime.
</P>
<P>
"NMD system would put in question the Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty(ABM) which is repeatedly referred to by both States Parties
as being a cornerstone of strategic stability," the Minister said.
</P>
<P>
"There is a risk that such actions jeopardize this balance,
and have negative consequences for nuclear disarmament and non-
proliferation,' the Minister said.
</P>
<P>
She called on the States Parties to refrain from any
deployment that could create uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
 Welcoming Russia's ratification of the START II Treaty, the
Minister expressed deep concern that it still has not entered into
force seven years after being signed and that negotiations on
START III are not yet underway.
</P>
<P>
 "The Russian Federation and the United States must now assume
their special responsibility, bring START II and its protocol into
force without further delay and immediately begin negotiations on
a START III treaty," she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
