<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile's Exports to Asia Go Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Asia is the main receiver of
Chilean exports in this year's first quarter, absorbing 32.6
percent of total exports, according to a report presented by this
country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, in such period, Chile's exports to
the Asian continent came to 1.578 billion U.S. dollars,
increasing by 33.5 percent, copper sales being the most dynamic.
</P>
<P>
Europe, meanwhile, is the second area of great importance,
accounting for 26 percent of Chilean exports. The amount destined
for this continent reached 1.258 billion dollars in the same
period, a rise of 13.3 percent with regard to a similar period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Chile's exports to the rest of Latin America
went up 23.8 percent, enjoying as main destination Brazil, with
236.9 million dollars, a rise of 83.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meantime, toward South Common Market (Mercosur), Chile's
exports reached an increase of 34 percent, ascending to 409
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sales to member countries of the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA) increased by 16.6 percent, with the income of 1.
171 billion dollars. With 967.9 million dollars, United States is
the largest importer within the group.
</P>
<P>
Sales of this South American country to Mexico went up by 21.6
percent, arriving at 162.4 million dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
