<HEADLINE> Sino-African Cooperation Hailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRETORIA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese President Jiang
Zemin voiced here Tuesday evening his confidence that the African
rejuvenation will become a reality in spite of the difficulties
that the continent currently faces.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks at a banquet hosted by South African
President Thabo Mbeki in honor of Jiang, who is on a state visit
to the country.
</P>
<P>
Jiang cited the African renaissance idea advocated by President
Mbeki as the common aspiration of the African people for peace,
stability and development.
</P>
<P>
"This idea will contribute to greater cohesion, strength and
economic revival of African countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Africa is the biggest developing continent and china the
biggest developing country, Jiang said, adding that "similar
historical experiences and common tasks have linked us closely
together."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it is of strategic significance for China and
Africa to enhance consultation, expand common ground, support each
other and increase cooperation under the banner of South-South
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"To this end, the Chinese government has proposed to convene
the forum on China-Africa Cooperation -- Ministerial Conference
Beijing 2000 in October this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that this meeting will inject new vitality to
the friendship and cooperation between China and Africa," Jiang
added.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is the last leg of Jiang's five-nation tour, which
has brought him to Israel, Palestine, Turkey and Greece. He also
met with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in the Alexandria city
of Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
