<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Students Protest Conservative Crackdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Iranian students on Tuesday took to
the street to defend the freedom of speech as the powerful
conservatives have intensified crackdown on the reformists and
their publications.
</P>
<P>
Students from Khajeh Nassir Tussi Technical University in Tehran
held a demonstration calling on President Mohammad Khatami to pay
more attention to the attempts underway to obstruct the reform
process in the country, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Elected Majlis (parliament) member Ali Akbar Musavi Khoeini
delivered a speech to the students, who issued a five-point
resolution in support of the reformist press and freedom of the
press.
</P>
<P>
The agency did not say how many people participated in the
demonstration while witnesses put the number at around 1,000.
</P>
<P>
Students also reportedly rallied at Tehran University overnight
after the conservative judiciary ordered the closure of 13
reformist dailies and periodicals, including two most popular
dailies--Fath (Conquer) and Asr-e Azadegan (Times of the Freed).
</P>
<P>
The closure of another prominent reformist daily Sobh-e Emrouz
(This Morning) was revoked later Monday night as its managing
director, Saeed Hajjarian, is still hospitalized after being shot
in an assassination attempt on March 12.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives, who control most of the country's powers,
suffered serious setbacks in elections in the past two years. They
seemed determined to revenge their humiliating defeat in the
February parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
The conservative watchdog Guardians Council announced on Tuesday
that it found errors in vote-recount in Tehran, where the
reformists won 29 of 30 seats in the elections. It has already
deprived seven elected reformists of their eligibility.
</P>
<P>
The reformists were expected to take over the Majlis on May 28,
but the new Majlis can officially start its work only after a
minimum of 190 parliamentarians were confirmed by the Guardians
Council.
</P>
<P>
If the election results in Tehran are nullified, the new Majlis
must wait until the result of the run-off.
</P>
<P>
The Special Court for Clergy, also dominated by the
conservatives, issued an arrest warrant against the reformist
cleric Hassan Yussefi Eshkevari for his participation in a
conference on Iran in Berlin, Germany.
</P>
<P>
Eshkevari was charged with "actions against national security,
propaganda against the system, insult to and rejection of the
absolute sanctities of Islam, and behavior not befitting the
clergy."
</P>
<P>
Eshkevari, a supporter of Khatami's reform policies, was among a
group of reformist invited to the controversial Berlin conference
titled "Iran After February Elections."
</P>
<P>
Hard-liners have organized rallies throughout the country over
the past few days to denounce the Berlin conference and increase
pressure on the reformists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Thins out Military Presence in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Syrian army has thinned out its
presence in the Bekaa valley in central Lebanon, As Safir newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Syrian army vacated its checkpoint at the entrance to the
village of Labwi, northeast of Baalbek, on Saturday and another
checkpoint at the entrance to the town of Brital, stronghold of
Maverick Shiite Muslim cleric Sobhi Tufaili, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper reported that six similar checkpoints were removed off
the Beirut-Baalbek highway on Friday, leaving a total of only three
Syrian checkpoints in the Bekaa region.
</P>
<P>
No explanation was given for the reduction of checkpoints and
the redeployment of Syrian troops in the Bekaa, which followed
Israel's formal declaration that it will withdraw from occupied
south Lebanon by July. Syrian army had earlier lifted several
checkpoints off the streets of the Lebanese capital of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Syria has deployed about 35,000 troops in Lebanon ever since
1976. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Conservative Watchdog Find Errors in Vote- Count </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Guardians Council, dominated
by the conservatives, announced Tuesday that it found serious
differences while recounting votes of the February parliamentary
elections in Tehran constituency.
</P>
<P>
The election watchdog hinted that it may nullify the polling
result in the Iranian capital, where reformists allied with
President Mohammad Khatami won 29 of the 30 seats in the first
vote-counting.
</P>
<P>
"The serious differences between the recount and the previous
result were unprecedented in elections and cast a shadow over the
whole result," the council said in a statement, released by the
official Islamic Republic News Agency.
</P>
<P>
It suspected that some of the vote boxes had been opened and
votes inside changed in the constituency, the biggest and most
important one in the country. But it gave no evidence or proof.
</P>
<P>
The reformists won a landslide victory in the parliamentary
elections in February, which was humiliating to the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
The Guardians Council last week ordered another recounting of
some boxes in Tehran constituency, apparently in response to
accusations of election irregularities.
</P>
<P>
The council's announcement comes amid mounting conservative
crackdown on reformist press. The judiciary have closed down 13
reformist publications on Sunday and Monday and sent several
reformist publishers and journalists to prison at the same time.
</P>
<P>
The council said that it has confirmed the eligibility of 185
elected for the upcoming sixth, 290-seat Majlis (parliament), but
nullified that of nine others from seven constituencies.
</P>
<P>
The result of Tehran constituency will be announced soon and a
run-off for the remaining seats will be held within two weeks, the
council said.
</P>
<P>
The reformists were expected to take over the Majlis on May 28,
but the new Majlis can officially start its work only after a
minimum of 190 parliamentarians were confirmed by the Guardians
Council.
</P>
<P>
If the election results in Tehran is nullified, the new Majlis
must wait until the result of the run-off.
</P>
<P>
The council's depriving nine reformists of their eligibility
aroused a series of protests, which, however, were drowned by a
nationwide conservative condemnation of reformists and their deeds.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives blast the reformists for advocating "U.S.-
style reforms in Iran." The supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei,
rejected "U.S.-style reforms" and vowed to defend the Islamic
values and principles.
</P>
<P>
He further accused the reformist press of becoming "enemy
strongholds" inside the country.
</P>
<P>
The reformists hit back by accusing the conservatives of trying
to prevent the formation of the new Majlis and undermine the reform
process of the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
