<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1 Iraqi Killed in U.S., British Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A truck driver was killed Tuesday
in U.S. and British warplanes' attacks on northern Iraq, an Iraqi
military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 10:45 (0645 GMT), eight formations of
U.S. and British planes made 16 armed sorties over northern Iraq
and bombed two villages, Al-Erbeid and Abu Nashka, in addition to
the Al-Eidan filling station in the northern Neiveva province.
</P>
<P>
The driver, identified as Tahsein Hussein Mohammad, was killed,
and the truck he was driving was badly damaged, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that at 10:50 (0650 GMT) and 17:00 (1300
GMT) on Tuesday, 21 formations of U.S. and British jets made 28
armed sorties from bases in Saudi Arabia and 17 armed sorties from
bases in Kuwait, overflying the southern Iraqi provinces of Basra,
Misan, Thi-Qar, Qadissiyah, Wasit, Muthana and Najaf.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi air defense artillery challenged the enemy planes and
forced them to flee back, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. and Britain launched the Operation Desert Fox air
strikes against Iraq in December 1998, their warplanes have made a
total of 20,601 armed sorties, 16,799 from bases in Saudi Arabia
and Kuwait, 3,802 from bases in Turkey, over the two so-called no-
fly zones in northern and southern Iraq, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's attacks came at a time when Iraq lodged strong
protests to the United Nations over the continued U.S. and British
raids against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In two letters, one to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the
other to president of the U.N. Security Council, Iraqi Foreign
Minister Mohammad Said Al-Sahaf said that 295 Iraqi civilians have
been killed and 860 others injured in the regular bombings of the
U.S. and British planes on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British warplanes patrol the two no-fly zones in
what they maintain as an effort to protect the Kurds in the north
and Shiite Muslims in the south from "possible persecution of the
Iraqi government."
</P>
<P>
Iraq does not recognize the air exclusion zones for their lack
of explicit authorization from the U.N. Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
