<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Sounds Warning to Pro-Israeli Militia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A leader of the Hezbollah
guerrillas on Monday warned the pro-Israeli Lebanese militiamen
that they would face reprisal if they stay on after the scheduled
Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon, As Safir newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hassan Nasrallah, secretary general of Lebanese
Hezbollah, said in an interview with Iran's official Islamic
Republic News Agency that the loyalty of the South Lebanon Army
(SLA) was to Israel, not to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"We do not regard the SLA as a Lebanese group. And if its
members stay behind in their position after the Israeli withdrawal,
this is regarded as aggressive action requiring a reply in the form
of resistance operations," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They either face trial for their acts or should leave the
country alongside their departing Israeli masters," he added.
</P>
<P>
Nasrallah said the SLA militiamen were Lebanese "only on paper"
and their long term plans were to serve the interest of not
Lebanon, but Israel.
</P>
<P>
If the SLA militiamen remained in Lebanese territory after the
(Israeli) pullout, they would be doing so to achieve Israeli
objectives, Nasrallah was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The SLA, funded and controlled by Israel, helps the Jewish state
patrol the 850-square-kilometer zone it has occupied in south
Lebanon since 1985.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian and Syrian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, and
other resistance forces are waging a war of attrition to end SLA
and Israeli control over south Lebanon, the last active Arab-
Israeli battle front.
</P>
<P>
Israel has formally declared that it will withdraw from occupied
south Lebanon by July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
