<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Falls Again In April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer confidence fell in
April after declining in March and February, the Conference Board
said in a survey Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board, a New York-based prominent research group,
said its Consumer Confidence Index is now 136.9 down from a
revised 137.1 in March.
</P>
<P>
"The recent volatility of the financial markets has clearly had
little, if any, impact on consumer confidence," said Lynn Franco,
Director of the Conference Board's Consumer Research Center. The
stock market has dropped sharply in recent weeks with the
technology heavy Nasdaq index falling in the bear market.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, while consumers rate current economic conditions less
positively than last month, their short-term outlook has improved.
The boost in optimism, coupled with tax refunds, should continue
to fuel spending."
</P>
<P>
Consumer sentiment is a barometer of the U.S. economy since
consumer spending makes up about two-third of the nation's
economic activity. The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates
five times since last June in an effort to curb consumer spending
which is viewed by the central bankers as an inflation trigger in
the hot economy.
</P>
<P>
The survey said consumer's appraisal of ongoing conditions was
less positive in April than in March. The percentage of
respondents that rated business conditions as "good" declined to
44.5 percent from 45.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of survey participants that claim jobs are "hard to
get" rose to 12 percent in April from 10.6 percent in March and
consumers who fell jobs are "plentiful" fell to 52.4 percent from
53.35 percent.
</P>
<P>
But optimism about the short-term outlook rose among consumers
in April, the survey said, adding that the percentage expecting
business conditions to improve during the next six months rose to
15.1 percent from 14.8 percent in the previous survey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
