<HEADLINE> Greece Reiterates Stand Over Aegean Differences With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Greece Tuesday reiterated its
position on its disputes with neighboring Turkey over the eastern
Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
In response to the recent statements by the Turkish Foreign
Minister Ismail Cem and Turkish armed forces chief Hussein
Kivrikoglu, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said at a
press briefing that only the Aegean's continental shelf ranked as
an issue to be resolved between the two neighboring countries in
the specific maritime region.
</P>
<P>
Reppas stated that Greek-Turkish disputes must be dealt with
through peaceful procedures without the use of force or the threat
of the use of force.
</P>
<P>
If Turkey believed that there were problems it could appeal to
the International Court of Justice at the Hague, he added.
</P>
<P>
For decades, Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have been
at odds over their differences in the territorial waters, air
space limits and the delimitation of the continental shelf in the
Aegean.
</P>
<P>
The Greek side maintains that the only difference separating
the two countries in the Aegean is the issue of the sea's
continental shelf.
</P>
<P>
Since last June, the two long-time rivals have begun to take
steps to improve their strained relations by the holding of a
series of bilateral talks and the signing of a number of
agreements for bilateral cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
