<HEADLINE> COMESA Urged to Set Up Security Mechanism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has called on the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) to carefully
scrutinize the implications of establishing a COMESA mechanism on
peace and security by avoiding the duplication of duties.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Minister Kelly Walubita made this remarks when
he officially opened the first meeting of the COMESA committee on
peace and security in Lusaka on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Walubita observed that the duplication of duties and conflict
of interests between organizations should be avoided.
</P>
<P>
He noted that COMESA was a sum total of member states which
belonged to other sub-regional groupings adding that those groups
had already formed similar organs to deal with matters of peace
and security hence the need to avoid duplication of duties.
</P>
<P>
The Minister called upon the participants to look at the gaps
which other regional groupings had not covered and consider ways
in which COMESA could address them in search for lasting solutions
to peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the participants to recognize and consider
the important work and roles of the various systems of the United
Nations (UN) and the Organization of African Unity (OAU) with a
view to finding ways in which COMESA could play a role in the
maintenance of peace and security in the world.
</P>
<P>
Walubita urged the participants to explore modalities through
which COMESA could work together with other regional organizations
such as the Southern African Development Community (SADC) on
issues of peace and security.
</P>
<P>
He noted that peace, security and political stability were
vital preconditions for regional economic development and
integration.
</P>
<P>
"Vital aspects of regional economic integration and
development, such as free movement of goods, services, capital and
persons, cannot be attained in an environment of instability."
</P>
<P>
"We do not need to be reminded of the impact of conflicts on
our economies among which are displacement of persons, creation of
refugees and the destruction of the environment," he said.
</P>
<P>
And addressing the same meeting, COMESA Secretary-General
Erastus Mwencha observed that half of the COMESA member states was
involved in armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
He said as a result of those conflicts, the COMESA member
states would find it difficult to meet their goals because the
free movement of goods, capital and persons in the COMESA region
would be impeded by conflicts.
</P>
<P>
He however noted that Zambian president Frederick Chiluba was
already involved in the mediation of peace talks in the Democratic
Republic of the Congo while Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi had
also undertaken missions to Ethiopia and Eritrea as part of the
overall OAU peace strategy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
