<HEADLINE> Habitat to Hold Preparatory Committee Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Center for Human
Settlements (Habitat) will host a preparatory committee session
here during May 8-12 this year in preparation for the U.N.
Conference on Human Settlements (or the City Summit) scheduled for
June 2001.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release issued here by the Habitat on
Tuesday, approximately 700 ministers, mayors and representatives
of non- governmental organizations from around the world are
expected to meet at the Habitat headquarters in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The preparatory committee session is to be held in response to
the second City Summit held in Istanbul in 1996, where 171
governments adopted the Habitat Agenda to highlight the importance
of urbanization and the role of cities.
</P>
<P>
During the next year's City Summit, the Habitat said, these
same governments will not only review and appraise the
implementation of the Habitat Agenda, but also present their
achievements on the promises they made in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
During the coming committee session, the delegates will focus
on the scope of the review and appraisal process, and introduce
new and innovative ways in which to manage the problems of
urbanization.
</P>
<P>
Klaus Toepfer, Acting Executive Director of the Habitat, said
that over three billion people or half of humanity now live in
cities and towns, which means that the future of the planet is
closely linked to the successful management of our urban areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
