<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Summit on Fighting Malaria Opens in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The first ever African summit on
fighting malaria opened Tuesday in the Nigerian capital Abuja,
attended by leaders from more than 40 African countries and dozens
of international agencies.
</P>
<P>
Opening the one-day summit aimed at refocusing attention on
malaria, Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo said the devastating
death toll from malaria in Africa called for a total cancellation
of the continent's debt to free resources to combat the deadly
disease.
</P>
<P>
"The gravity of the malaria problem with all its ramifications
provides a strong case for the forgiveness of all African debts,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the heads of state to implement a plan of
action aimed at reducing the incidence of malaria by half in
Africa by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika said in his
capacity as head of the Organization of African Unity that African
leaders could not remain indifferent faced with this challenge of
malaria.
</P>
<P>
Malaria, a mosquito-borne disease, is said to be a major cause
of human and economic underdevelopment in Africa. Current United
Nations statistics indicate that malaria kills at least one
million people each year, some 90 percent of them in African
countries.
</P>
<P>
The record also shows that "nearly 500 million people suffer
globally from acute malaria, 90 percent of the burden taking place
in Africa."
</P>
<P>
However, malaria is preventable and curable. The most effective
way is to avoid being bitten by mosquito which carries the
parasite.
</P>
<P>
The summit, proposed by Obasanjo last year, is co-sponsored by
the World Health Organization, the United Nations Children's Fund,
the United Nations Development Program, the World Bank and the
African Development Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: African Summit on Fighting Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from more than 40 African
countries met in Nigeria's capital Abuja on Tuesday to make
strategy to confront one of the top killers across the African
continent -- malaria.
</P>
<P>
The one-day African summit on malaria, proposed by Nigerian
President Olusegun Obasanjo last year, was co-sponsored by the
Nigerian government and four United Nations agencies: the World
Health Organization (WHO), the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF), the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) and the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released by the WHO recently, malaria
kills one child every 30 seconds in the world, with Africa getting
most of the death toll.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that malaria kills over one million
people each year globally, with 90 percent of the victims in
African countries.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,500 African children under the age of five die from
malaria every day; and whereas the disease is on the retreat in
other continents, it is spreading across Africa.
</P>
<P>
Malaria has worsened the already daunting poverty relief
situation in the African continent, where some two billion U.S.
dollars were lost annually due to the disease and related ones in
recent years, the UNDP said.
</P>
<P>
It said some families in African countries had to spend an
average of one-quarter of their income on malaria treatment.
</P>
<P>
According to Jeffrey Sachs, a renowned American economist who
is also in Abuja to attend the summit, the cost of malaria,
including lost work time and money, reduces the growth rate of
most sub-Saharan African countries by more than one percentage
point each year.
</P>
<P>
African nations have been making concerted efforts to contain
the human and economic scourge caused by the disease and their
efforts culminated in the endorsement of the Harare Declaration on
Malaria by African leaders in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
Their efforts were boosted by the WHO, UNICEF, UNDP and the
World Bank in 1998 when they jointly launched the Roll Back
Malaria Initiative. It was in order to further concretize the two
sides' cooperation that President Obasanjo proposed a summit on
the initiative.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, African leaders are expected to call on Western
governments and companies to step up their research into a vaccine
for malaria.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, international organizations have been on a
campaign for wider use of cheaper means to combat the disease such
as specially treated bed nets and effective medicines.
</P>
<P>
With a greater commitment from governments and donors, to the
distribution of mosquito bed nets and effective drugs the WHO
believes it can attain its target of reducing the incidence of
malaria by half in Africa by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that whatever declarations made at the Abuja
summit will be submitted to the next meeting of Organization of
African Unity (OAU) for adoption and implementation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
