<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Conservative Watchdog Find Errors in Vote- Count </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Guardians Council, dominated
by the conservatives, announced Tuesday that it found serious
differences while recounting votes of the February parliamentary
elections in Tehran constituency.
</P>
<P>
The election watchdog hinted that it may nullify the polling
result in the Iranian capital, where reformists allied with
President Mohammad Khatami won 29 of the 30 seats in the first two
vote-counts.
</P>
<P>
"The serious differences between the recount and the previous
result were unprecedented in elections and cast a shadow over the
whole result," the council said in a statement, released by the
official Islamic Republic News Agency.
</P>
<P>
It suspected that some of the vote boxes had been opened and
votes inside changed in the constituency, the biggest and most
important one in the country. But it gave no evidence or proof.
</P>
<P>
The reformists won a landslide victory in the parliamentary
elections in February, which was humiliating to the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
The Guardians Council last week ordered a third recount of some
boxes in Tehran constituency, apparently in response to accusations
of election irregularities.
</P>
<P>
The council's announcement comes amid mounting conservative
crackdown on reformist press. The judiciary have closed down 13
reformist publications on Sunday and Monday and sent several
reformist publishers and journalists to prison at the same time.
</P>
<P>
The council said that it has confirmed the eligibility of 185
elected for the upcoming sixth, 290-seat Majlis (parliament), but
nullified that of nine others from seven constituencies.
</P>
<P>
The result of Tehran constituency will be announced soon and a
run-off for the remaining seats will be held within two weeks, the
council said.
</P>
<P>
The reformists were expected to take over the Majlis on May 28,
but the new Majlis can officially start its work only after a
minimum of 190 parliamentarians were confirmed by the Guardians
Council.
</P>
<P>
If the election results in Tehran is nullified, the new Majlis
must wait until the result of the run-off.
</P>
<P>
The council's depriving seven reformists of their eligibility
aroused a series of protests, which, however, were drown by a
nationwide conservative condemnation of reformists and their deeds.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives blast the reformists for advocating "U.S.-
style reforms in Iran." The supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei,
rejected "U.S.-style reforms" and vowed to defend the Islamic
values and principles.
</P>
<P>
He further accused the reformist press of becoming "enemy
strongholds" inside the country.
</P>
<P>
The reformists hit back by accusing the conservatives of trying
to prevent the formation of the new Majlis and undermine the reform
process of the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia, Iran Keen to Maintain Stable Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia and Iran have
voiced keenness to maintain stable bilateral relations and forge
good ties between Iran and other Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
states, the Saudi Press Agency monitored here reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement made Monday night in the western Saudi city of
Jeddah, Saudi Second Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Defense
and Aviation, Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz, said Riyadh is "
supporting good relations and cooperation between Iran and the GCC
states, especially the United Arab Emirates (UAE)."
</P>
<P>
The statement was made in a joint press conference after the
prince's meeting with visiting Iranian Defense Minister Ali
Shamkhani.
</P>
<P>
Both Abu Dhabi and Tehran declared sovereignty over the isles of
Abu Musa and the Greater and Lesser Tunbs, located in the mouth of
the strategic Strait of Hormuz. The islands are now controlled by
Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi prince voiced hope that the dispute would be settled
through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Shamkhani, who arrived in Jeddah Monday as the
first Iranian defense minister to visit Saudi Arabia since the 1979
Islamic Revolution, asserted that "the common geographic, historic
and cultural aspects of Iran and Saudi Arabia necessitate the
development of bilateral ties."
</P>
<P>
He also stressed keenness on strengthening relations, based on
mutual understanding, between Iran and the Arab countries,
including the GCC states--Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi
Arabia and the UAE.
</P>
<P>
Shamkhani said Iran is earnestly looking forward to the visit of
Defense Minister Sheikh Bin Rashid al-Maktoum of the UAE, the first
GCC country that Shamkhani had visited.
</P>
<P>
Shamkhani is expected to meet later in the day with Saudi King
Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz and Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Saudi Arabia were in mistrust and discord for nearly
two decades because of Tehran's former policy of exporting the
ideology of its 1979 Islamic Revolution which toppled the late
shah's regime and brought about the clergymen's rule.
</P>
<P>
Their relations warmed up after Iran's moderate President
Mohammad Khatami took office in August 1997 and adopted a policy of
detente.
</P>
<P>
The past years have witnessed steady improvement in relations
between the two big Gulf powers in the political and economic
fields.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian defense minister is now in Saudi Arabia to "
negotiate a comprehensive agreement on security cooperation."
</P>
</TEXT>
