<HEADLINE> Over 200 Million Dollars For Indian Drought Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The central government of India
has released 9.5443 billion rupees (222 million U.S. dollars) as
assistance to four major states hit by severe drought this summer,
an official release said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Center is constantly monitoring the situation and
coordinating efforts to mitigate the hardships being faced by the
people due to the drought," said the release.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, as many as 9,421 villages in 17
districts of the western coastal state of Gujarat, 23,406 villages
in 26 districts of the northwestern state of Rajasthan, 17,431
villages in 18 districts of Andhra Pradesh on the southeastern
coast and 3,240 villages of seven districts in the central state
of Madhya Pradesh have been affected by the summer drought.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Ministry of Railways also announced on Tuesday free
transportation of fodder and water to Gujarat and Rajasthan, which
were believed to be the most severely afflicted by the calamity,
to save cattle there from dying from starvation and thirst.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Agriculture Ministry has requested chief
ministers of neighboring states, such as Haryana, Madhya Pradesh,
Maharashtra, Punjab and Uttar Pradesh, to help Gujarat and
Rajasthan in arranging supply of fodder on a priority basis,
government sources said on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
