<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Social Policy in Asia Faces More Challenges (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua ) -- Social policy in the Asia-
Pacific region has become more difficult with the ever-growing
population, increased globalization and technological advancement,
a group of senior Chinese and foreign social policy researchers
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Researchers also urged policy-makers in the region not to stay
complacent but be ready to break away from conventional paradigms
and search for innovative ways to address the ever-changing needs
of the community.
</P>
<P>
The ever-growing population of the Asia-Pacific region "will
inevitably bring about new challenges to governments," said
Secretary for Hong Kong Health and Welfare Department E. K. Yeoh
when addressing the opening ceremony of the Conference on
Repositioning the State: Challenges and Experiences of Social
Policy in the Asia-Pacific Region in Hong Kong Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that the population of the region will
increase from 3,693 million in mid-1999 to 4,523 million in 2020.
</P>
<P>
"And at the same time, two new factors - the increased
globalization and technological advancement - are increasingly
affecting the way in which we live and which will have an ever-
significant impact on social policy," Yeoh stressed.
</P>
<P>
Increased globalization means greater inter-state interaction
and interdependency, and technological advancement, in terms of
information technology and e-commerce, will open new opportunities
and present challenges for the delivery of social services
throughout the region, Yeoh explained.
</P>
<P>
As part of the global economy, the Asian financial turmoil
swept over Hong Kong, making its impact felt in the form of
negative economic growth, high unemployment, deflation and a
depressed property market, Yeoh said, adding that this has
inevitably resulted in the emergence of a host of social problems.
</P>
<P>
"The globalization will exert massive negative impacts not only
on the domestic social inequality but the enlarging of the
international gap between the developed and developing countries,"
said Guan Xinping, professor of China's Nankai University, in his
speech entitled "China's Social Policy in the Context of
Globalization."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Social Policy in Asia Faces More Challenges (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Researchers believed that the European welfare state's golden
age in the early post-war years was under the condition of a
protected economy, which no longer functioned well after the 1970s
when more free trade and less restriction to capital's free
movement began to be implemented into the world economy by GATT's
negotiation mechanism.
</P>
<P>
They warned that the most of the Asian countries are more
vulnerable to any global crisis since they are a kind of exports-
based, open economies.
</P>
<P>
In a more open economy, the government faces pressures both
from the enlarging of its social welfare programs to deal with the
increasing urban unemployment and poverty caused by the
international competition and from the reduction of its social
expenditure in order to strengthen the economic competitiveness of
the country, Guan said.
</P>
<P>
After the future accession into the WTO, China's social policy
has to face more challenges than ever before, including stronger
international competition, increasing average income, higher
inequality and more poverty, higher demand in social protection,
and further restructuring of economic and social systems, as well
as the rapid aging population.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day discussion, researchers also suggested a
number of different measures to meet the future challenges in view
of different political and economic conditions of each country and
area in the region.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, the most pressing tasks are reforming the welfare
subvention system, developing a strategic needs assessment
mechanism, defining the role of individuals, families, the
community and the government, strengthening inter-sectoral
collaboration amongst various policy-makers and agencies, and
reforming the health care sector, they said.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, gender has become an important factor in social
politics in recent years, and it is now at the center of the
welfare state restructuring debate, according to Ito Peng, an
associate professor from the School of Policy Studies of Kwansei
Gakuin University in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Peng said that the post-war Japanese welfare state has
continuously shifted its positions on public child care by
weighing the country's economic needs for women's labor against
the various fiscal and demographic pressures.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the Japanese government has no choice but to
consider ways to reconcile the contradiction of conservative and
highly gendered welfare state to extend social welfare,
particularly those related to the care of the young and the old,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Examining the income transfer to the elderly in the Republic of
Korea and China's Taiwan, Huck-ju Kwon, assistant professor of the
Sung Kyun Kwan University in Seoul, said that urgent policy is
necessary to prevent further deterioration in the living standard
of the elderly, especially in the wake of the economic crisis, and
public transfer will play a bigger role than now as the public
pension programs in the Republic of Korea come into full operation
in due course.
</P>
<P>
In China, researchers suggested that efforts should be made to
quicken the pace of the development of non-profit organizations in
all fields of social welfare, saying it has played an ever
important role since the country introduced the policy of reforms
and opening to the outside world. They called it the "third sector.
"
</P>
<P>
Over 30 scholars on social policy from Japan, the Republic of
Korea, China's mainland and Hong Kong and Taiwan, as well as other
countries and areas attended the two-day event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians, Israel Discuss Interim Phase Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian and Israeli negotiators
concluded another round of talks on the interim-phase issues in the
West Bank city of Jericho Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
During their two-hour meeting, the two sides discussed the
release of more Palestinian prisoners from Israeli jails, the
opening of a northern safe passage linking the West Bank and Gaza,
and the possibility of building another Palestinian airport in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
They also tackled economic and financial cooperation in
accordance with the interim Sharm el Sheikh agreement signed last
September in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Saeb Erekat, head of the Palestinian team, told reporters after
the meeting that the Israeli side promised to consider the list of
prisoners the Palestinians asked to be released.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, a top Palestinian official disclosed that
the Palestinian side would demand Israel to set free 230 prisoners,
including the elderly, the sick and those jailed prior to the
establishment of the Palestinian autonomous regime in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,600 Palestinians are still detained by Israeli
authorities.
</P>
<P>
On the airport issue, Erekat said the Palestinians prefer the
old tarmac in Kalandia to the north of Jerusalem to a new port in
Jericho. Gaza International Airport was opened for civil aviation
about a year and half ago to be the sole air transport outlet in
the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed on every thing regarding Gaza harbor and the
construction process will kick off soon," Erekat said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Sharm el Sheikh deal, the construction scheme in Gaza
sea port should have started early last October but was put off due
to lack of funds and the obstacles laid by the Israeli side.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, chief Israeli negotiator Oded Eran said "We may reach
an agreement over what we discussed today in two weeks from now."
</P>
<P>
The two sides, moreover, signed a joint message to be conveyed
to the United States Administration, asking for a 50-million-U.S.-
dollar aid to carry out the projects of the interim phase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat, Jordanian King Discuss Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
visiting King Abdullah II of Jordan discussed the latest
developments of the Middle East peace process, particularly on the
Palestinian track, and bilateral ties in the West Bank city of
Ramallah Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
According to Voice of Palestine radio, Arafat briefed Abdullah
on his recent talks in Washington with United States President Bill
Clinton, while the Jordanian King outlined his Sunday meeting with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in Eilat, southern Israel.
</P>
<P>
In a joint news briefing with Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel
Ilah al-Khatib following the meeting, Palestinian Minister of
International Cooperation Nabil Shaath said the summit was "
important and positive," particularly as it took place after
Arafat's Washington trip and Abdullah's recent visits to Egypt and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Palestinian National Authority called for
an inclusive solution to all issues of the final-status talks with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that the Israeli side was not prepared in
this period to sign a final-status framework agreement which
involves such thorny issues as the fate of Jerusalem, borders,
Palestinian refugees, Jewish settlements and water.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib hailed the "distinguished" Jordanian-Palestinian ties,
reiterating Jordan's firm support for the Palestinian cause and the
establishment of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah's visit to Palestine came within the continued
consultations between the two sides, he said, stressing that Jordan
has been pursuing a just and fair peace in the Middle East to the
common benefit of all parties.
</P>
<P>
King Abdullah returned home after the brief visit in the company
of Queen Rania and a number of top Jordanian officials. Arafat
awarded his guest the collar of "Bethlehem 2000" in appreciation
for the king's support for the Palestinian cause.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Barak in Eilat, Abdullah stressed that
the Palestinian issue is the core of the Arab-Israeli conflict,
suggesting that Jerusalem could be a joint capital of Israel and
the future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Another round of Palestinian-Israel final-status talks is due to
kick off in Eilat on April 30 in a bid to conclude the framework
agreement in advance of a final peace treaty tabled to be signed
next September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
