<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Continues Attack on Abu Sayyaf Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government troopers
moved in closer Tuesday to the lairs of the Abu Sayyaf group which
holds hostage some 28 people, as air strikes continued in Mt.
Punoh Mahajid in the southern Province of Basilan, the authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the Southern Command of the Armed Forces of the
Philippines (AFP) in Zamboanga city said in a statement that a
communication tower and two generators in the Abu Sayyaf camp were
destroyed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They said three government troopers were killed in the initial
assaults and three others wounded. Meanwhile, government troopers
recovered 14 high-powered guns in the area left behind by Abu
Sayyaf extremists.
</P>
<P>
Southern Command Chief Major Gen. Diomedio Villanueva said the
operations will continue.
</P>
<P>
The military launched massive rescue operations last Saturday
and is continuing its assault, involving artillery and air attacks
in support of ground troops, said to be closing in against the
kidnap group.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, truck-loads of Citizens Armed Forces Geographical
Unit (CAFGU) members have also been mobilized by Basilan Governor
Wahab Akbar to augment military troopers.
</P>
<P>
The augmentation of the CAFGU personnel came after the military
suffered several casualties due to lack of knowledge of the
terrain in the province.
</P>
<P>
Akbar said the deployment of the auxiliary forces is to finish
the rescue operation the soonest time possible.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the AFP is giving itself until Wednesday to finish
the operations to rescue the 28 remaining hostages being held by
the Abu Sayyaf since March 20.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have warned they will behead their five remaining
male hostages, including a priest, if the military does not halt
its assault.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who announced last week that they had beheaded two
male hostages, have demanded the freeing of Arab terrorists held
in jails in the United States, including the mastermind of the
1993 World Trade Center bombing.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf is the smaller but more radical of two Muslim
groups fighting for an independent Islamic state in the southern
Philippines. It has been blamed for numerous attacks on Christians.
</P>
</TEXT>
