<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Parliament Approves Chemical Weapons Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's Parliament Tuesday
approved a bill designed to implement the country's obligations as
a signatory to the 1993 Convention on the Prohibition of the
Development, Production, Stockpiling and Use of Chemical Weapons
and on their Destruction (CWC).
</P>
<P>
The CWC is the result of 20 years of negotiations in the United
Nations Conference on Disarmament and it has been ratified by 129
countries including the United States and Russia. Singapore signed
the CWC in 1997 and ratified it in the same year.
</P>
<P>
In his second reading speech, Singapore Minister for Foreign
Affairs S. Jayakumar said that besides the obvious security
benefits in a world that is free of chemical weapons, there are
also other advantages to ratification.
</P>
<P>
As a member of the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical
Weapons (OPCW) established by the CWC, he said, Singapore can
obtain technical assistance from other member countries if
threatened with an attack by chemical weapons and ratification is
also expected to facilitate trade in chemicals which are
controlled by the Convention.
</P>
<P>
Jayakumar told parliament that the bill will have a limited
impact on the commercial operations of Singapore's companies in
the chemical and other industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
