<HEADLINE> Russian Federal Troops Rebuff Fresh Rebel Ambush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian federal troops on Tuesday
rebuffed a fresh ambush mounted by rebels in the breakaway
republic of Chechnya, a ranking military official said.
</P>
<P>
A federal serviceman was wounded in the one-hour fighting when
his armored personnel carrier was hit, but the rebels were
subsequently "dispersed and partially eliminated," said Colonel
General Valery Manilov, first deputy chief of the Russian General
Staff.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's attack came just two days after another rebel ambush
that killed 13 federal servicemen.
</P>
<P>
The federal military convoy, which consisted of a unit of a
reconnaissance battalion and a motorized infantry company, was
moving from Urus-Martan to Shatoi when the ambush took place.
</P>
<P>
The rebels attacked the column about four kilometers from the
so-called Wolf Gates at the entrance to the Argun gorge near the
village of Yaryshmardy.
</P>
<P>
"The column instantly responded by launching an artillery
counterattack against the rebels' revealed firing positions. Mi-24
helicopter gunships urgently arrived at the scene and delivered a
strike against the rebel positions," Manilov said.
</P>
<P>
Russia launched the military campaign last September following
waves of armed Chechen incursions into neighboring Dagestan and a
spate of terrorist bombings that killed over 300 people in Moscow
and two other cities.
</P>
<P>
With most of Chechnya under federal control and only pockets of
rebel formations in the southern mountains, the Russian military
has declared that the military phase of the campaign has completed.
</P>
<P>
The accent is now being shifted to special operations, Manilov
said, noting that a little over 3,000 rebels remain in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
He said that the federal forces have killed 13,500 rebels since
August, including over 2,500 rebels that died between August and
October in the fighting in Dagestan and other areas bordering
Chechnya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
