<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Officials Checks Beijing's Flood-Control Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Jirao, Chinese vice
minister of water resources, today inspected Beijing's water
control facilities and urged the importance of preparations for
possible flooding.
</P>
<P>
Zhang and officials from the State Flood Control and Drought
Relief Headquarters inspected the flood discharge and holding
projects in the Shijingshan, Fengtai, and Fangshan districts and
Daxing County in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that Beijing, the national capital, is prone to
floods and has been frequently struck by flood disasters through
history.
</P>
<P>
The importance of the anti-flood works in the Haihe River
Valley, which covers Beijing, Tianjin, and Hebei Province, cannot
been underestimated, Zhang stressed.
</P>
<P>
His inspection will continue through April 28 in Tianjin and
Hebei.
</P>
<P>
Major dykes protecting downtown Beijing were reinforced after
the floods of 1998, the country's second worst flood disaster year.
Beijing has given this year's flood control priority to the
dredging of river courses.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's water control officials have been devoted to both
flood prevention and drought relief efforts, since the capital
began suffering a severe drought at the start of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
