<HEADLINE> U.S. Agriculture Secretary Confident of China Trade Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of
Agriculture Dan Glickman expressed his confidence this evening
that the U.S. Congress will grant China Permanent Normal Trade
Relations status.
</P>
<P>
"My judgment is that it will pass, but it will be a close vote,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary, accompanied by four congressmen and one governor,
arrived here this evening to underline the importance of Permanent
Normal Trade Relations for China to U.S. political, economic,
trade, and security interests in China and East Asia.
</P>
<P>
In an arrival statement, Glickman said that "this is my fourth
visit to China" and this is a "presidential mission," adding that
President Clinton told him the "importance of this visit" when he
saw him off.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China has taken extraordinary steps to open the
country and economy to the outside world, and now is preparing to
join the World Trade Organization and become integrated into the
global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
"I believe, and the president believes, that it is an
opportunity we cannot let get away," Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
"We are here to educate ourselves to better understand China,
its economy, its society and its people," he said, adding that he
hopes U.S.-China friendly cooperation will score more achievements
in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Glickman said he will meet Chinese entrepreneurs tomorrow
afternoon, and will speak with local U.S. Chamber of Commence
members in Beijing, Shanghai, and Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
