<HEADLINE> Highlights of Diplomatic News Today (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi said at the regular
press conference that he believes the National People's Congress (
NPC) of China will quicken the process of ratifying the
Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
 U.S. Urged to Grant China PNTR Status
</P>
<P>
The U.S. side should take concrete measures to approve
Permanent Normal Trade Relations for China in time and without any
conditions, otherwise it will greatly harm the interests of
American companies in China, said Sun.
</P>
<P>
 New Japanese PM Urged to Respect History
</P>
<P>
Sun urged the newly-elected Japanese prime minister to take
lessons from Japan's history of invasion.
</P>
<P>
China has always hoped that Japan take the path of peace and
development, and treat its past history of invasion with proper
recognition and a right attitude, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
Thorough Investigations on Embassy Bombing Urged
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government demands that the U.S. government conduct
comprehensive and thorough investigations into its bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia, and bring the perpetrators to
justice, said Sun.
</P>
<P>
 China's Non-Proliferation Stand not Changed
</P>
<P>
China's position on nuclear non-proliferation is consistent and
has not changed, according to Sun.
</P>
<P>
 Danish PM to Visit China
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen of the Kingdom of Denmark
will pay an official visit to China from May 7 to 14, announced
Sun.
</P>
<P>
 Swedish Deputy PM to Visit China
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Lena Hjelm-Wallen of the Kingdom of
Sweden will pay a visit to China from May 7 to 13 at the
invitation of Vice Premier Wu Bangguo.
</P>
