<HEADLINE> Oil to Be Main Source of Fuel in 15 Years: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Oil will be the main source of
transportation fuel for at least the next 15 years, and demand for
it is expected to increase in the transportation sector, predicted
a Kuwaiti energy expert Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Demand for oil in the transportation sector, especially in the
emerging economies in southeast Asia will increase by 4.5 percent
annually, said Dr. Mohmmed Al-Ramadan, executive assistant to the
managing board director of Kuwait Petroleum Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ramadan said this growth rate will offset the possible drop
in demand in the industrial countries who might begin using other
types of energy for their means of transportation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, oil will be the main source of fuel for 90
percent of cars within a 15-year period, as it will grow more
important that cars turn to use other types of fuel in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti expert said that in the past century global energy
consumption in the transportation sector, which rose by 2.7 percent
annually during 1971-1992, constituted half of the world oil
consumption.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the increased energy consumption in
transportation has led to environmental problems such as air
pollution and global warming.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ramadan hailed the efforts in the last couple of years to
protect the environment and reduce dependence on oil.
</P>
<P>
He said these efforts stressed on developing technology for
alternative means of ground transportation and discovering other
sources of energy than oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Keep its Nuclear Policy Ambiguous: Deputy DM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Israel will maintain its
strategy of ambiguity on the nuclear weapons issue, with neither
acknowledgment nor denial of the possession of nuclear weapons,
Israeli Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by Israeli Army Radio, Sneh said that Israel has
followed the nuclear opacity policy for years in a formula that
Israel will not be the first country to introduce nuclear weapons
into the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
"We don't say what we have or don't have, which leaves others to
keep guessing. It is good that this will remain so in the future,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Sneh was commenting on the ongoing United Nations review
conference of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT), which
opened at the U.N. headquarters in New York on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, which was aimed to prevent the spread of nuclear
weapons and technology, was signed in 1970 and is subject to
reviewing every five years.
</P>
<P>
At the 1995 NPT conference, it was extended indefinitely by a U.
N. landmark resolution, making it permanent.
</P>
<P>
Israel, the only country in the Middle East that has not signed
the NPT, did not dispatch delegations to attend the four-week
conference as observer, fearing that it will be singled out in the
forum as the major threat to a nuclear-weapon-free zone in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Issam Mahoul, an Israeli Arab legislator who initiated an
unprecedented session of Israeli parliamentary debate on the
nuclear issue in February, said that Israel has 200 to 300 nuclear
warheads.
</P>
<P>
Since The Sunday Times of London published photos about Israel's
nuclear reactor in the Negev Desert town of Dimona in 1986, which
revealed that Israel has the sixth largest nuclear arsenal in the
world, the nuclear capability of Israel has been a worst kept
secret.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, competing with Israel for dominant military role in the
region, has launched a campaign at the NPT conference to secure a
special condemnation of Israel for its refusal to sign the treaty.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian delegation to the gathering includes two most
prominent nuclear disarmament experts, its ambassadors to Geneva
and Tokyo. The Egyptians are expected to address the conference on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In response to the development, Sneh said on Tuesday that
Egypt's behavior to undermine Israel's position at the conference
is unacceptable, antagonistic and unfriendly.
</P>
<P>
Sneh hoped that the United States, the major patron of Israel in
the world political arena, will side with Israel to defend Israel's
policy on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
