<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Create New Body to Look Into Transport Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Tuesday that the Presidential Palace will soon create a new body
to look at the whole issue of the country's transport safety.
</P>
<P>
The government's move comes following the April 19 crash of Air
Philippines Flight 541 in Samal Island near Davao City that killed
all l31 passengers and crew aboard.
</P>
<P>
Press Secretary Ricardo Puno told reporters that the new
independent body will have the same functions as those of the
National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB).
</P>
<P>
The NTSB, according to Puno, is a standing body created by law,
which automatically springs into action every time there is an
accident, whether it's a fatal or a non-fatal mishap or an aborted
takeoff in the case of airplanes.
</P>
<P>
Since the most recent incident involved air transportation,
Puno said the new body will initially cover the air safety
situation.
</P>
<P>
"Eventually it might also go to sea transportation and
eventually into land. But the details are now being worked out
with Secretary Vicente Rivera of the Department of Transportation
and Communication," Puno said.
</P>
<P>
He also made it clear that it is still the Air Transportation
Office that will handle the investigation of the Samal Island
crash and come out with the results of the inquiry in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
Puno said the creation of the body is a calculated effort which
will eventually result in some kind of an exhaustive appraisal of
the transportation situation in the country, including the various
carriers involved, their practices and their equipment, the air
controllers system, and airport facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
