<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, S. Africa Sign Cooperative Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRETORIA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China and South Africa expressed
their determination to further bilateral relations by signing a
declaration on the partnership between the two countries and six
other documents here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The declaration, signed by visiting Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and South African President Thabo Mbeki, is aimed at
publicly stating the guiding principles for the bilateral ties in
order to coordinate and integrate the wide spectrum of the
government-to-government relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The declaration announced the establishment of the Bi-National
Commission between the two sides to consult on matters of mutual
interest in the bilateral and multilateral spheres.
</P>
<P>
The other six documents include agreements on bilateral
maritime transport cooperation, phytosanitary cooperation,
cooperation in animal health and quarantine, cooperation in the
fields of arts and culture, the avoidance of double taxation and
the prevention of fiscal evasion with respect to taxes on income,
and police cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese President began a state visit to South Africa on
Monday, the last leg of his five-nation tour which has brought him
to Israel, Palestine, Turkey and Greece. Jiang also met with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in the Egyptian city of
Alexandria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
