<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Farmers Call for WTO Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Zambian farmers are seeking the
support of the World Trade Organization (WTO) for subsidies to
enable them to compete effectively with farmers in developed
countries, Times of Zambia newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Zambia National Farmers Union (ZNFU) president Ajay
Vashee as saying his organization was seeking protection from the
WTO against the continued unfair practices where the farmers in
the industrialized world are being heavily subsidized on the
global market.
</P>
<P>
Vashee, speaking before leaving for the United States to attend
a WTO meeting, hoped that the world trade body put in place
measures that would help developing countries stand competition.
</P>
<P>
He said that the current trend that the farmers in the
developed world were heavily subsidized was detrimental to
agricultural producers in the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the WTO will put in place practices that will help the
farmers in the developing countries to continue producing since
our countries are denying subsidies under the auspices of
liberalization," Vashee noted.
</P>
<P>
The Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA)
assistant secretary-general Sindiso Ngwenya last month also
stressed the need for developing countries to consider subsidizing
their agriculture sector to enable them to compete effectively
with the industrialized world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
