<HEADLINE> China Increases Money Supply to Support Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Maintaining a balance between the
prevention of financial risk and the promotion of economic growth
is now at the top of the agenda for the central bank's monetary
committee.
</P>
<P>
The committee members met in Beijing recently and agreed that
great efforts will be made to boost the development of the country
's capital market and to accelerate the market-oriented reform of
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The central bank will utilize a variety of monetary tools to
support economic growth and to increase the money supply
moderately in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter, China witnessed an 8.1 percent economic
growth rate, and its broad money supply (M2) surged 13 percent
over the 1999 figure, with the narrow money supply (M1) jumping 18.
7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the exchange rates of the Chinese yuan remained
stable because of continuous growth of the country's foreign
exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
The committee said that Chinese banks will continue financing
infrastructure and technological upgrading projects, most of which
are funded with state debt, as well as promoting the development
of western China.
</P>
<P>
The central bank reiterated that the current financial policy
forbidding banks and securities companies from stepping into each
other's businesses was still in line with conditions in China.
</P>
<P>
The panel also suggested that the People's Bank of China (PBOC),
the China Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC), and the China
Insurance Regulatory Commission (CIRC) meet regularly to
coordinate arising issues.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, central bank governor and committee chairman,
presided over the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
