<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Algeria achieved a trade surplus of 1.98 billion U.S.
dollars in the first three months this year, against 202 million
dollars in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the Algerian Customs Administration showed that the
volume of exports in the first three months hit 4.06 billion
dollars, up by 76.17 percent from the same period 1999. Meanwhile,
the volume of imports dropped by 1.19 percent to 2.08 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Oil and gas exports accounted for 98 percent of the total
exports with 3.98 billion dollars, up by 80.1 percent from 2.21
billion dollars during the first three months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Gulf countries hold a medicine market share of 30
percent of the Arab world in spite of the fact that their
population only account for 10 percent of the total Arab
population.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Corporation for Industrial Investment said in a report
that the number of pharmaceutical factories in Gulf countries
surged from 11 in l990 to 31 in 1999, up by 181 percent. And the
invested capitals and work force in this industry jumped by 191
percent and 107 percent respectively during the same period.
</P>
<P>
The number of pharmaceutical factories in the Arab countries
stood at 195 by 1998, covering more than 40 percent of the market
which witnessed a boom in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The OHS consortium, responsible for the 501-kilometer
Turkish section of the Russian-Turkish Blue Stream Natural Gas
Pipeline, is taking special measures to ensure the safety of the
pipeline as it crosses the Ladik Fault Line in Samsun, north of
Turkey, reported the Anatolia News Agency on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Field testing of a design to protect the pipeline from the
effects of earthquakes will be completed by this summer.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the pipeline is progressing rapidly and the
full 501 kilometers of pipes and ancillaries are expected to be
completed by the end of July this year.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Palestinian Airways will open twice-weekly flights
from Gaza to Istanbul from June 1, reported Turkish Daily News on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The flights will depart on Mondays and Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
The air carrier, symbolic of Palestinian statehood, was
established two years ago, thanks to the Oslo peace agreement
reached between Israel and the Palestine Liberation Organization
(PLO) in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
