<HEADLINE> Thai Soldier Dies in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A Thai soldier participating in
the United Nations peacekeeping mission in East Timor died last
week from a heart failure and prolonged intestinal problems, Thai
News Agency (TNA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An army spokesman was quoted by TNA as saying that sergeant 1st
class Sutat Soamdi died on April 17 when he was receiving
treatment at a medical unit of the Thai mission in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Sutat was about to be sent back to Bangkok to continue his
treatment when he abruptly died, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The body of Sutat was flown home on Saturday by a Malaysian
flight, and was cremated on Monday in his hometown Lop Buri
province in central Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The soldier's wife and his nine-year-old daughter will receive
a military insurance worth 100,000 baht (2,666 U.S. dollars) and
other special funds from the Royal Thai Army and financial
assistance from the United Nations, the spokesman said. 
</P>
