<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Finds No Trace of Sabah Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Tuesday that it still faces a blank wall in its search for the 18
foreigners and two Filipinos kidnapped by unidentified gunmen
Sunday in a beach resort in Sabah, Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said concerned
cabinet members held an emergency meeting to discuss the Sabah
hostage crisis because of reports that the kidnappers were
Filipinos and the victims were possibly brought to southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Mercado told reporters that acting Armed Forces chief of staff
Jose Calimlim briefed the meeting on the on-going search and
rescue operations of the kidnap victims.
</P>
<P>
"We went through the information we have gathered so far. In
our evaluation of the information we have concluded that there's
nothing we can confirm as of the moment as to the identities to
those who perpetrated this particular crime," Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
He also said neither could the authorities pinpoint where the
victims were brought.
</P>
<P>
He said the authorities expected the kidnappers to emerge to
make an announcement of their demands. "Whether it is for
political purposes or financial reasons, they will have to ask for
concession," Mercado added.
</P>
<P>
The victims, mostly foreign tourists, were snatched by some six
gunmen in the beach resort of Sipadan island, Sabah, Malaysia last
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Two reconnaissance planes of the Philippine Air Force and
several Philippine Navy ships combed the nearby Sulu Sea since
Monday to intercept the boat-riding kidnappers but there was no
trace of the victims, Calimlim said.
</P>
<P>
Calimlim also said he did not believe a claim by the Abu Sayyaf
terrorists that they were responsible for the kidnapping in Sabah.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf is under siege by the military in Basilan
province where the Muslim extremists are holding 27 civilian
hostages they abducted on March 20.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who announced last week that they had beheaded two
male teachers, have demanded the freeing of Arab terrorists held
in jails in the United States, including the mastermind of the
1993 World Trade Center bombing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
