<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SIA Secures Acquisition of 25 Pct of Air N.Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Airlines (SIA)
Tuesday announced that it had reached an agreement with the
Brierley Investment Limited (BIL) to acquire 16.7 percent of Air
New Zealand, bringing to 25 percent its total holding in the New
Zealand's national carrier.
</P>
<P>
An announcement from SIA said the purchase is in the form of "B
" ordinary shares for 285 million New Zealand dollars (240
Singapore dollars or 141 million U.S. dollars) based on a price
of three New Zealand dollars per share.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came after SIA purchased 8.3 percent of the share
capital of Air New Zealand in the form of "B" ordinary shares for
141 million New Zealand dollars (120 Singapore dollars or 70.5
million U.S. dollars) on April 11, 2000.
</P>
<P>
With 25 percent of Air New Zealand, SIA will have a strategic
stake in both Air New Zealand and the Ansett Holdings Limited (
Ansett), Australia's No.2 carrier, as the New Zealand carrier
already owns 50 percent of Ansett and will acquire the other 50
percent soon.
</P>
<P>
A press release from SIA said the acquisition is subjected to a
number of conditions, including regulatory approvals, due
diligence, and Air New Zealand completing its acquisition of the
remaining 50 percent of Ansett.
</P>
<P>
If these conditions are satisfied, the transaction is expected
to be finalized by mid-2000, it said.
</P>
<P>
The press release quoted SIA Deputy Chairman and CEO Cheong
Choong Kong as saying:" As evidenced by our recent 49 percent
stake in Virgin Atlantic, SIA's objective is to become a global
group of airline and airline-related companies. This stake in Air
New Zealand and, indirectly, Ansett is another important step
towards the goal." SIA and Virgin announced that SIA would take a
49 percent stake in Virgin last December.
</P>
<P>
"The investment consolidated the commercial alliance created by
SIA, Air New Zealand and Ansett in 1997," Cheong was quoted as
adding.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said SIA was eyeing a 40 percent stake in the
New Zealand Airlines but it has no way to achieve the target as
New Zealand law bars a foreign airline from owning more than 25
percent of a domestic carrier. Under the law a group of airlines
can only own up to 35 percent stake in its carrier.
</P>
<P>
The reports also said buying into Air New Zealand which is soon
to take control of Ansett seems to shut off any likelihood of SIA
partnering Virgin in Australia despite Virgin hoped SIA would join
it in its planned no-frills Australian airline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Takes Measures for Prostitute Rehabilitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
taken up a social welfare plan in four districts -- Dhaka, Jessore,
Mymensingh and Rajbari -- to rehabilitate prostitutes under "
Prostitutes Rehabilitation Project," the official Bangladesh News
Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Social Welfare Department (SWD) will implement the plan
with the
financial help of the United Nations Development Program.
</P>
<P>
At the first stage of the plan, 4,435 prostitutes will be
rehabilitated, Side Coordinator of the Project Shamsul Alam said,
adding that necessary medicines, health education, sanitation
facilities and vocational training will be provided to the
rehabilitated prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
At the second stage, they will be employed according to their
qualification and ability, so that they can live self-reliantly.
The SWD has appointed a non-government organization to discharge
responsibility in the field service on behalf of the SWD.
</P>
<P>
Recently the SWD has appointed four coordinators for the four
districts. Each coordinator will at first form a committee
consisting of public-elected persons and government officials,
which will conduct surveys on the numbers and condition of the
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
The government will provide necessary training and loans to the
prostitutes who want to lead a simple, normal social life.
</P>
</TEXT>
