<HEADLINE> Canadian Railway Reports 41 Percent Profit Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Canadian National Railway Co.(CN)
reported Monday a 41 percent rise in profit for the first quarter
of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Montreal-based company said its profit reached 196 million
Canadian dollars (about 133 million U.S. dollars) for the first
three months, compared with 139 million Canadian dollars (about 94
million U.S. dollars) for the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In the period, the company's revenue rose 8 percent to 1.4
billion Canadian dollars (about 948 million U.S. dollars) from 1.3
billion Canadian dollars (about 880 million U.S. dollars) for the
first quarter of last year, with the company's operating ratio --
expenses as a percentage of revenue -- improving to 72.2 percent
from 76.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
CN's operating income totaled 382 million Canadian dollars (
about 259 million U.S. dollars) in the first quarter, up 29
percent over the same period of 1999 and the highest the company
has ever seen in the period.
</P>
<P>
Share profit for the first quarter of 2000 increased to 96
cents (about 0.65 U.S. U.S. dollars) from 72 cents (about 0.49 U.S.
dollars in the same period of last year, said the company,
attributing the improvement to continued cost controls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
