<HEADLINE> China Eastern Airlines Reaps 24.37 Pct Revenues Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China's leading aircraft
services provider, the China Eastern Airlines Corporation Limited,
Tuesday announced a revenues increase of 24.37 percent to 10.16
billion RMB (1.23 billion U.S. dollars) for 1999, thanks to the
economic recovery of the Asian region.
</P>
<P>
The group, which suffered a net loss of 481 million RMB (58.16
million U.S. dollars) in 1998, said its attributable profit to
shareholders was 151 million RMB (18.26 million U.S. dollars) for
the year ended December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Traffic volume grew by 27.48 percent to 1.84 billion tonne-
kilometers. Average aircraft daily utilization increased by 0.4
hours to 8.1 hours compared with the previous year. Passenger
traffic grew 21.72 percent to 13.25 billion passenger kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of Eastern Airlines Li Zhongming attributed the good
performance to a remarkable increase in the passenger traffic
volume in both domestic and international flights as a result of
the recovery of the Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
"In particular, tourism in (South) Korea and Southeast Asian
region has grown which helped improve the Group's performance,"
said Li.
</P>
<P>
"Strengthened market supervision by the Civil Aviation
Administration of China (CAAC) and the regulation of domestic
pricing of airfares also helped by stabilizing the airfares," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
