<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-President Meets Former Japanese Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao
said today that statesmen of China and Japan should approach
bilateral relations from a long-term and strategic perspective.
</P>
<P>
Hu made the remarks here in a meeting with former Japanese
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and former Director-General of
the Economic Planning Agency Shusei Tanaka.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president also stressed that consensus and cooperative
agreements reached by Chinese and Japanese leaders should be
earnestly implemented, statesmen of the two countries should
promote exchanges and mutual understanding, eliminate problems and
obstacles, and make new contributions to Sino-Japanese friendship
geared toward the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
He said that adherence to the principles enshrined in the Sino-
Japanese Joint Statement, the China-Japan Treaty of Peace and
Friendship and the China-Japan Joint Declaration as well as
correct understanding and treatment of such issues as historical
facts and the Taiwan issue are the political basis for the smooth
development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that high-level exchanges of visits between the two
countries have been frequent in recent years, and the two
countries have reached important consensus and opened up prospects
for bilateral cooperation in a variety of areas.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-president also praised Hosokawa's efforts to
promote Sino-Japanese relations during and after his tenure.
</P>
<P>
Hosokawa said that bilateral relations have been developing
quite smoothly since the normalization of relations between the
two countries. Of course, he added, there have been some twists
and turns along the way. He said he hoped that any difficulties
will be overcome and bilateral relations will continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
Hu and Hosokawa also discussed ways to further promote Sino-
Japanese friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese guests are here at the invitation of the Chinese
People's Institute of Foreign Affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
