<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet to Help Introduce Traditional Medicine Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The combination of the Internet
and traditional Chinese medicine (TCM) will provide convenience
and high-speed access for people seeking treatment using
traditional medicine.
</P>
<P>
"It has already become an inevitable trend that the
traditional Chinese medicine will enter the world with the help of
Internet," said Qian Guofeng of the Hong Kong TCM Network Company
Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Compared with western medicine, TCM has advantages in treating
chronic non-infectious diseases which are related to psychological
and social factors as well as diseases common among elderly people.
It can improve people's immune system with less side effects and
costs less. But these advantages are still not fully recognized by
western countries.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the major reasons for this are the slow
spread of information on TCM and basic cultural differences. It is
difficult for foreign people to accept theories of TCM which are
completely unlike those held by western medical professionals.
</P>
<P>
Qian suggested that the Internet be used to spread facts about
TCM to people across the world, and to provide information on
state policies, research findings and commercial events about TCM,
along with educational resources, available medical treatment and
e-commerce to professional personnel.
</P>
<P>
If the documents and literature on TCM produced over the past
several thousand years can be put into computers and get online, a
large human information resources center will be formed, said
Professor She Jing with the China State Administration of
Traditional Chinese Medicine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Intensify Supervision over Customs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature has vowed
to stamp out smuggling by increasing the power of customs and to
stop corrupt activities of customs officials by supervising them
more closely.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Keyu, a vice-chairman of the National People's Congress (
NPC) Law Committee, delivered the message in a report on the
revision of the Law on Customs to the 15th meeting of the NPC
Standing Committee, which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Many NPC Standing Committee members want to add a clause in the
draft which says: "Customs and their staff should accept
supervision by supervisory departments when they conduct their
administrative law-enforcement; anti-smuggle police should accept
supervision by people's procuratorates when they conduct
investigations."
</P>
<P>
Another suggested clause reads: "Auditing departments conduct
auditing and supervision on the financial income and expenditure
of customs in accordance with law, and have the right to carry out
special auditing and investigation on matters that are related to
the financial income and expenditure of the State."
</P>
<P>
Zhou said the NPC Law Committee and the Commission of
Legislative Affairs of the NPC Standing Committee had sent
investigation teams to Guangdong, Yunnan and Hainan provinces to
gather suggestions from official departments and foreign trade
companies.
</P>
<P>
It is imperative that the existing customs law be revised to
meet the needs of China's further opening up to the rest of the
world, setting up a modern customs system, cracking down on
smuggling, and ensuring the healthy development of the socialist
market economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
The NPC law committee proposed that an anti-smuggling public
security department be set up in the General Administration of
Customs, which will be composed of special anti-smuggling police.
If necessary, the customs anti-smuggling public security
department could ask public security departments of the State
Council to direct and coordinate other police forces to help deal
with smuggling cases, the committee proposed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
