<HEADLINE> Chinese Army Promotes Younger Officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Guangzhou Military Area
Command of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA) has promoted
a large number of younger officers to senior positions as part of
the effort to prepare the army for the new century.
</P>
<P>
After the latest promotions, the average ages for commanders at
corps and division levels in the Guangzhou Military Area Command
are 50.1 and 43.6 years, respectively. The youngest commanders at
corps, division and brigade levels in China's southern military
area stand at 46, 41 and 36 years, respectively.
</P>
<P>
These young officers have been promoted because of their high
morals and abilities, according to sources at the military area.
</P>
<P>
Forty-six percent of the officers at or above regiment levels
are university graduates or hold a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
The military area has demobilized many older officers to make
way for younger ones, many of whom have been assigned to combat
units from non-combat divisions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
