<HEADLINE> Nigerian Diplomats Suffering Liberian War to be Compensated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Seven officials of the Nigerian
foreign service are to be paid a total of some 125,000 US dollars
by the government in compensation for loss sustained during the
seven-year civil war in neighboring Liberia, reported the News
Agency of Nigeria Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Agency quoted a senior official of the service as saying
that the compensation is for the loss of their belongings during
the outbreak of violence in 1996 when their homes were invaded by
fighters loyal to Charles Taylor, then leader of the national
patriotic front of Liberia, one of the factions in the country's
civil war.
</P>
<P>
During the invasion, the affected officers lost all their
belongings and were only saved following the intervention of the
Nigeria-led West African Peace Keeping Force or ECOMOG in that
country.
</P>
<P>
Nigerians, whose country provided the bulk of the regional
peacekeeping force, were frequently the targets of violent attacks
during the seven year war which ended with internationally
supervised elections in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
