<HEADLINE> British Boxer Lewis Threatens Belt Bust-up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Lennox Lewis is considering giving
up his WBC and IBF heavyweight titles, following a contract row
with promoter Don King.
</P>
<P>
Lewis said he is so fed up with boxing's rulers that he is
considering handing back his remaining belts.
</P>
<P>
The Briton, whose win over Evander Holyfield last November
unified the heavyweight division and made him the undisputed king
of world boxing, had his WBA title taken away after a court battle
with King.
</P>
<P>
And Lewis claims he is so disenchanted at being told whom he
can and cannot fight he is contemplating throwing his titles back
into the ring and taking on whoever the boxing public want him to.
</P>
<P>
Lewis, set to fight Michael Grant in New York in defence of his
WBC and IBF titles on Saturday, said: "I have thought seriously
about giving up my titles - why should I fight who the
organisations tell me to when some decisions are clearly
influenced by fight promoters and managers?
</P>
<P>
"I might as well give back the belts and just get into the ring
with whoever the public want me to face. They are the guys who
matter; they pay the price of a big ticket on a big fight night or
phone the TV company to watch on pay-per-view," he told The Sun
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"Let the public choose. Their voices should be heard. They
want real fights, not fights that have been engineered," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
