<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Launch New Benchmark Indexes for IT Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Hang Seng Index (HSI)
Services Limited Tuesday announced it will launch two new indexes
on April 26 to meet the increasing demand for a benchmark to gauge
the performance of the information technology (IT) and
telecommunications sector of the local stock market.
</P>
<P>
The two new indexes, the Hang Seng IT Index (HSITI) and the
Hang Seng IT Portfolio Index (HSITP), have been devised to meet
different investors needs in view of market skewedness towards a
small number of stocks in the IT sector, Vincent Kwan, general
manager of the HSI Services Limited, told a media briefing Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng IT Series of Indexes are backdated to April 1,
1999, with a base value of 1,000 for each index. The HSITI index
and HSITP index stood at 2,754.18 and 3,448.80, respectively, at
the close of business on April 20, 2000,
</P>
<P>
"Information technology and telecommunications companies are an
increasingly important sector of the local stock market," Kwan
said.
</P>
<P>
The market value of the HSITI's constituent stocks increased by
193 percent during the year ended April 20, 2000, compared with 32
percent for constituents of the benchmark Hang Seng Index, 59
percent for H-shares and 43 percent for China-affiliated companies
during the same period, according to Kwan.
</P>
<P>
"As at April 20, the market value of these stocks accounted for
29 percent of the total market capitalization of the Stock
Exchange of Hong Kong (SEHK), and turnover of the HSITI stocks
also increased by 311 percent over the past 12 months," Kwan noted.
</P>
<P>
Kwan said both the new indexes comprise the same constituent
stocks but with different weightings. The constituents of the
HSITI are weighted at their full market capitalization based on
the total number of shares issued, while weightings of HSITP are
adjusted so that no stock will have a weighting exceeding 20
percent in the index, he said.
</P>
<P>
Weightings will be rebalanced at the end of each month, and the
new indexes cover 18 stocks listed on either the main board or
Growth Enterprise Market of the SEHK, Kwan said.
</P>
<P>
Eligible constituents must belong to one of the sub-sectors,
including fixed-line and wireless telecom services, computer
hardware and services, semiconductors, telecom equipment, Internet,
software, and e-commerce, which are selected among the information
technology and telecommunications classification groups of the
FTSE Global Classification System, an internationally recognized
stock classification system, he explained.
</P>
<P>
The indexes will be released daily from April until May 12,
2000, and from then onwards, the indexes will be released every 15
seconds on each trading day, Kwan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Ends Slightly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks closed
slightly higher Tuesday in thin trade volume, amid the weakness of
technology shares and a disappointing government land auction.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Hang Seng Index edged up 12.87 points, or 0.08
percent, to close at 15,380.01 with the turnover of only 7.001
billion HK dollars (898 million U.S. dollars), as against the
previous trading volume of 7.590 billion HK dollars (973 million U.
S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the overall market was quiet as investors took a
wait-and-see attitude. There was some dumping of high-tech shares
early in the afternoon, followed by some buying of old economy
blue chips.
</P>
<P>
Of the four sub-indices, Finance, Utilities and Properties
gained 0.40 percent, 0.67 percent and 0.28 percent, respectively,
while Commerce and Industry lost 0.19 percent.
</P>
<P>
Hang Seng China Enterprises Index went up 1.36 percent, while
the Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corp Index plunged 4.40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong stock market closed on Friday and Monday because
of the Easter holiday. The blue chips were down 31.25 points, or 0.
20 percent, to open at 15,335.89 Tuesday. The stock prices
rebounded slightly and closed the morning session at 15.425.74.
</P>
</TEXT>
