<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pilot Demobilization Project to Start in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia is to start a pilot
demobilization project in May in three provinces, according to a
press communique from the Council for Demobilization of Armed
Forces available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,500 soldiers will be demobilized under the program.
</P>
<P>
The demobilization program is going to start after the end of
the registration process for the armed forces, said Svay Sitha,
the secretary general of the Council for Demobilization of Armed
Forces. And a total of 15,551 ghost soldiers and 159,597 ghost
children were removed from the military payroll during the
registration and verification process.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project will see 250 soldiers being
demobilized in Kampot province and this will be followed by
another 460 in Kompong Thom a little later. Once the efficacy of
the pilot program in Kampot and Kompong Thom is determined, a
further 790 will be laid-off in Battambang and Banteay Meanchey.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces personnel to be demobilized are from the
special target group, comprising chronically ill soldiers,
disabled, elderly and some regular forces. Most of those who are
to be demobilized are already not staying in the barracks and have
returned to their respective community.
</P>
<P>
Each demobilized soldier will be paid Cambodian riel equivalent
to 240 U.S. dollars, and get some community related projects to
help them resettle back into civilian life, as well as the skills
training of their choice.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a total of 31,500 soldiers will be
demobilized from this year to 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
