<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Launch Speaker's Corner in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Minister for Home
Affairs Wong Kan Seng said Tuesday that the country's Speaker's
Corner is expected to be launched by the end of August this year.
</P>
<P>
Wong told the Parliament that the Speaker's Corner will be
operated with a minimum of rules, but speakers will be barred from
making speeches that will cause ill will or hostility among
different races.
</P>
<P>
"The speech should not be religious in nature, and should not
have the potential to cause feelings of enmity, hatred, ill will
or hostility between different racial or religious groups," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
"The police will adopt a minimalist, hands-off approach towards
the Speaker's Corner. The police will not try to control
activities there as long as there are no law and order problems,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
A speaker will not be allowed to use a microphone, but can
speak on just about anything he want, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
The Speaker's Corner will be located at Hong Lim Park, a venue
chosen because of its history and location, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Park, close to the Business District and Chinatown which
are areas of high concentration of people and activities, is also
historically the site for political rallies and speeches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
