<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Mark 17th World Candlelight Memorial to AIDS Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Uganda will join the rest of
world to mark the 17th International Candlelight Memorial on May
21, a day dedicated to people who have died of AIDS and those
living with HIV.
</P>
<P>
"The campaign against AIDS will bring together the people to
fight AIDS and value life," Margaret Egonda, an official with
Uganda AIDS Commission (UAC), told Xinhua in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
The national memorial to be held at Mandela Sports Stadium
Namboole in Kampala will include a symbolic bon-fire. Other
activities will include a procession through the city prayers,
talk-shows and newspaper supplements featuring stakeholders and
their tole in fighting AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"This campaign reminds us the importance of men and their
potential in contributing to the fight against the disease, and
the power they have in causing behaviour change," UAC Director
General Kihumuro Apuuli was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nearly two million Ugandans have been confirmed dead as a
result of HIV/ AIDS since the first case of AIDS was reported in
Uganda in 1982. The national AIDS prevalence rate was as high as
over 30 percent in late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Up to date the rate has dropped to 10 percent due to the
government's increasing efforts against the disease and great
enhancement of people's awareness in this regard. Uganda is the
only African country where AIDS prevalence rate is dropping, and
it aims to reduce the rate from the current 10 percent to 7.5
percent by the year 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
