<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Oil States Get Enlarged Revenue Share </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Federal government has
begun implementing a constitutional but delayed revenue
allocation formula which entitles nine of its 36 states to an
enhanced share of national oil revenue,
</P>
<P>
the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The NAN quoted Nigeria's Minister of State for Finance, Jubrin
Martins- Kuye as saying Monday that all the states are in the
country's south east, the location of its vibrant oil sector
which accounts for some 99 percent of national income.
</P>
<P>
The payment is expected to end the controversy over the
disbursement of the fund and pacify its oil producing areas,
particularly the Niger Delta which accounts for most of the some
3 million barrels of oil produced daily and which has recently
become the bedrock of violent agitations.
</P>
<P>
The country's 1999 constitution, which came into effect with
the inauguration of civilian government in may last year, entitles
the country' s nine oil producing states to 13 percent of the
revenue from oil from this January.
</P>
<P>
Jubrin said in a statement that 11.95 billion naira (119
million U.S. dollar), consisting of 7.53 billion naira (75 million
dollars) in arrears for the first two months and 4.41 billion (44
million dollars) for the month of march has been paid to the
states in fulfillment of this constitutional requirement.
</P>
<P>
The beneficiaries include the States of Abia, Akwa Ibom,
Bayelsa, Cross River, Delta, Edo, Imo, Ondo and Rivers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
