<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian House Speaker Lauds Regional Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The West African Parliament,
currently being canvassed by the sub-regional leaders, would
assist the region in solving some of the problems plaguing it,
said Speaker of Nigeria's House of Representatives, Alhaji Ghali
Umar Na'Abba Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Post Express, a leading Nigerian news paper Tuesday quoted
him as saying in Abuja, capital of the Africa's most populous
country that the move by the sub-region to integrate economically
would be more beneficial to countries with serious economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the question of economic and political integration
in the sub- region had been like the age long problem of the egg
and the chicken, which one comes first," noting that "the
political structure, in this regard, the West African Parliament
can contribute positively to more economic integration."
</P>
<P>
Na'Abba assured that with the introduction of the West African
 Parliament, most of the countries in the sub-region would be
brought closer for the exploration of each other's potential.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed fears being expressed by some member countries,
saying " there's no magic about these things. I want you to take
into account the size of Luxembourg in relation to Germany or
France. These countries like Luxembourg and Belgium are small
countries among larger ones. These together with the larger ones
believed they should belong to a union to achieve their aim."
</P>
<P>
Na'Abba criticized attacks by the newly elected President of
Senegal, Dr. Abdoulaye Wade on Nigeria, concerning the
integration of West African countries, stressing that "Nigeria
can contribute a lot to the establishment of this West African
union, in that the size of Nigeria would be an advantage to
smaller countries."
</P>
<P>
He said that the resources of Nigeria would also be at the
disposal of the smaller countries within the sub-region, adding
that " we have a lot of resources which between us we don't even
know about."
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the West African parliament which was
canvassed by the sub-regional leaders at their summit last year
in Togo, would be beneficial to the countries within the
sub-region, irrespective of size.
</P>
<P>
The President of Senegal had criticized Nigeria, saying other
West African countries should resist Nigeria's membership of the
West African Union following the intimidating size and population
of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
