<HEADLINE> Swedish Volvo Buys Trucks Unit of French Renault </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Swedish auto maker Volvo
announced on Tuesday it had bought the trucks unit of French
Renault, through which it could establish the second largest
camion producing group.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen percent of Volvo's shares, equaling 14 billion kronor (
1.6 billion U.S. dollars) will be transferred to Renault in
exchange of the trucks unit.
</P>
<P>
About 160,000 trucks of over 16-ton loading capacity will come
off line yearly in the newly-merged truck producing group, whose
size is the second largest in the world after the German-American
Daimler Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
The price of Volvo's shares rose by 5.6 percent to 215.50
kronor when trading began following the announcement of the merger.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, Renault said it will also buy five percent of
Volvo's to take its total holding to 20 percent and the amount of
five percent would cost about 500 million euros (470 million U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
