<HEADLINE> Turkish Ruling Coalition Proposes Presidential Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The leaders of Turkish ruling
coalition made a unanimous decision to recommend Ahmet Necdet
Sezer, chairman of the Constitutional Court, as their common
presidential candidate, the Anatolia News Agency reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said that Sezer has accepted the
offer made by the coalition partner parties following three rounds
of talks on Monday, which ran from 2.00 p.m. until 11.00 p.m. local
time.
</P>
<P>
Sezer was born in Afyon province in western Anatolia on
September 13, 1941. He was appointed as a member of the
Constitutional Court by former Turkish President Kenan Evren.
</P>
<P>
Sezer was responsible for a majority of the decisions made by
the Constitutional Court, including closure of the former Islamic
Welfare Party.
</P>
<P>
After officially announcing Sezer as a candidate of the ruling
coalition, Ecevit called for support from the main opposition
Virtue Party and True Path Party.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to receive the support of the two opposition parties in
this important matter of the state," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit dismissed claims that Sezer was a name from outside the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
"As the leaders of coalition partners parties, we have launched
an initiative sincerely. We were in an effort to find a solution on
behalf of Parliament as well as our own parties. Nobody has the
right to feel suspicion about our good will in this respect," he
said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the majority of deputies, regardless of
which party they belong to, are strongly against the nomination of
a candidate from outside Parliament.
</P>
<P>
If the oppositions fail to give support to Sezer, Ecevit said
that "We can think on it again. Now, all we think is that five
parties should act together. I have talked to the leaders of five
parties in my every step and have exchanged views with them."
</P>
<P>
According to the election procedure, the deadline for
presidential nominations expires at midnight on Tuesday as the
presidential election should be completed by May 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
