<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Court Issues Arrest Order for Reformer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Special Clergy Court (SCC)
on Tuesday issued an arrest warrant for reformist cleric Hassan
Yusefi Eshkevari for his participation in a conference in Berlin,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Eshkevari's charges were "action against national security,
propaganda against the system, insult to and rejection of the
absolute sanctities of Islam, and behavior not befitting the
clergy," Ebrahim Nekoonam, the SCC prosecutor general, told the
Islamic Republic News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said Eshkevari did not return to Iran after his participation
in the Berlin conference and that he will be detained as soon as he
returns home.
</P>
<P>
Eshkevari is a supporter of President Mohammed Khatami's reform
policies. He was one of a group of reformers that were invited to
attend the Berlin conference, titled "Iran After February
Elections."
</P>
<P>
The arrest order came amid a new wave of crackdown on the
country's reformist campaign by the powerful conservatives, which
has led to the closure of a dozen of reformist journals and jailing
of journalists.
</P>
<P>
Another prominent reformer, Akbar Ganji, was last Saturday for
attending the Berlin conference.
</P>
<P>
Ganji, a member the editorial board of reformist daily Fatah
(conquer), was sent to prison following several hours of
interrogation and after being informed of 10 complaints lodged
against him.
</P>
<P>
Hard-liners have arranged various rallies and demonstrations
throughout the country in recent days denouncing the Berlin
conference, organized by the Heinrich Boell Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The reformists were accused of advocating the U.S.-style reforms
in Iran at the conference, which was disrupted by members of
outlawed Mujaheddin Khalq Organization (MKO) who accused the
Iranian government of "crimes and human rights violations" in Iran
since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
Iranian conservatives, who dominate most of the sensitive organs
but suffered a severe setback in February's parliamentary election,
said that the Berlin conference was religiously prohibited and the
judiciary has assigned the revolutionary court to probe the case
against Iranian participants.
</P>
<P>
Iranian reformists defended the Berlin conference and accused
the conservatives of trying to use the conference as a pretext to
stop the new reformist-dominated parliament from meeting and
undermining Khatami's reform programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
