<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Search for Hostages Going on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The search party for 20
people taken hostage by gunmen from Sipadan island off Sabah, East
Malaysia, has swelled to several hundred men Tuesday, police
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The search party is scouring the waters on the Malaysian border
with Southern Philippines, Sabah Commissioner of Police Mamat
Talib said, according to Bernama news agency.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the hostages are not in Malaysian territory as we
are working with our counterparts in Southern Philippines to track
them down," Bernama quoted the commissioner as saying.
</P>
<P>
Both helicopters and fixed-wing aircraft as well as naval boats
are involved in the massive operation which entered its second day
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Six gunmen struck on Sipadan, one of the world's top diving
spots,on Sunday night and later sped off in two boats with 20
hostages, including 11 foreign tourists who are identified as two
each from France, South Africa and Finland, three from Germany and
one each from Lebanon and the Philippines, with the rest being
Malaysian workers on the island.
</P>
<P>
The police officer said the police had not received word from
the gunmen about demands in exchange for the release of the
hostages.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Malaysian Defence Minister Najib Tun Razak told
reporters here Tuesday that the hostages are now outside Malaysian
waters.
</P>
<P>
Declining to say whether the hostages are in Philippine waters,
Najib said Malaysia hoped for assistance from the Philippine
government to secure the safe release of the hostages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
