<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Aid Agency Calls for Concerted Efforts to Avoid Famine in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland's Development Agency
has urged the international community, donors and the local
authorities to co-ordinate their efforts to avoid a repeat of the
famine in 1984/1985 in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
There are pockets of food shortage in the north of drought-
striken Ethiopia and the local population are leaving their
settlements in search of food, Jurg Zumstein, program coordinator
for the Horn of Africa with the Development Agency, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On return from a fact-finding mission to Ethiopia, Zumstein
said that the situation could reach a crisis point if the rain
does not set in the next few weeks. Although the situation now is
not yet as widespread as in 1985, he said, it is critical because
the strategic reserves of grain have been used up and the stocks
need to be replenished to avoid a disaster.
</P>
<P>
"Ethiopia is one of the least developed countries in terms of
land transport," Zumstein pointed out, "Even if there is a surplus
of food, it can often not be brought to the markets."
</P>
<P>
Switzerland has pledged 4.5 million Swiss francs (about 2.7
million U.S. dollars) for humanitarian aid for the needy in
Ethiopia for the current year. More than half of the money will go
towards the United Nations World Food Program. The Disaster Relief
Unit also has experts in the region to help increase the capacity
of the port of Djibouti and improve the road network in Ethiopia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
