<HEADLINE> Olympic Organizers Keep Torch Relay Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Sydney's Olympic organizers (
SOCOG) said on Tuesday they would continue with their plans to
send the Olympic torch into space.
</P>
<P>
Strong crosswinds at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida had
prevented the launch of the flight carrying the Olympic torch into
space.
</P>
<P>
A replica of the torch and an Olympic flag were stowed inside
the space shuttle Atlantis, which was set to embark on a mission
to repair the international space station.
</P>
<P>
SOCOG officials were hoping the space mission, during which the
torch would orbit the earth 15 times a day for a week, would help
promote the official Olympic torch relay which starts next month.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a setback and it's not going to delay the start of
the relay," a SOCOG spokesman said. "SOCOG remains confident that
the torch will be in space in time to promote the start of the
Sydney 2000 torch relay." 
</P>
</TEXT>
