<HEADLINE> Japanese Volunteers Plant Trees In Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Some 500 local people together
with 145 volunteers from the northern Japanese province of
Hokkaido on Monday planted 2,500 saplings in the Sino-Friendship
Forest at a scenic spot in Fuxin City of northeast China's
Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The idea for the forest was initiated by Hokkaido Governor Hori
Tatsuya during Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to Japan in
November 1998.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the two countries reached an agreement on jointly
building the forest over a three-year period, starting from 2000.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Hokkaido volunteers are to travel to the
city to join their Chinese counterparts in planting 2,500 saplings
every year in the forest.
</P>
<P>
By 2002, they will have jointly planted 7,500 trees in the area,
meant to symbolize ever-lasting friendship between the Chinese and
Japanese people.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 Fuxin students, workers and government officials
planted trees with their Japanese guests.  
</P>
</TEXT>
