<HEADLINE> International Chain Businesses Favor China-Made Commodities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from over 200
international chain businesses are attending the on-going 87th
China export commodities fair in Guangzhou, capital of south China
's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
They include Wal-Mart, the world's retail giant based in the
United States, and William E. Connor &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
Tim Yatsko, a corporate executive with Wal-Mart, said the
quality of China-made commodities has continued to improve in
recent years, certain goods are available in wide varieties, and
the prices are comparatively cheaper.
</P>
<P>
He said Wal-Mart hopes to buy more China-made products and to
acquire more long-term commodity suppliers in China.
</P>
<P>
Wal-Mart will import 3.7 billion U.S. dollars-worth of goods
from China this year, Yatsko said, a rise over the three billion U.
S. dollars it spent last year on Chinese commodities.
</P>
<P>
William E. Connor &AMP; Associates is one of Asia's leading
purchasing agent companies, serving retailers and low-profit shops
from America, Europe, Australia and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mark J. Hayden, executive president of the company, told
reporters that they hoped to buy articles for daily use from the
fair, including home appliances, toys, footwear, ceramics and
hardware.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 types of commodities are on display at the 12-
day fair, which opened April 15.
</P>
<P>
A record of over 12.7 billion U.S. dollars worth of export
deals were sealed at last year's event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
