<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Situation Still Critical in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus had torrential downpours
during the last few days but the water situation on the
Mediterranean island is still critical.
</P>
<P>
According to Tuesday's Cyprus Mail newspaper, until Monday,
April 2000 was already being counted as one of the wettest April
since 1901 and the Meteorological Service of Cyprus was predicting
more rain for Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meteorological Service Director Cleanthis Philaniotis said this
month could yet prove wetter than the wettest April since the turn
of the last century, which was 1971, when 98 mm of rain fell
accross the island.
</P>
<P>
The average precipitation for the month is 30 mm.
</P>
<P>
After heavy rains every day since last Wednesday, the total
precipitation until Monday for this April reached 58.5 mm, some 196
percent of average.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus' Water Development Department, a total of 4.
2 million cubic metres of water rushed into dams between Thursday
and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This injection of water brought the total stored behind dam
walls to 46.6 million cubic metres, or 17.1 percent of the dam's
capacity. At the same time last year, reservoirs were about 26
percent full.
</P>
<P>
Water officials warned that the water situation in Cyprus
remains tragic and is unlikely to change, even if the rains
continue.
</P>
<P>
"We might exceed the 1971 record this year," Philaniotis said,
adding that April 2000 was already one of the 10 wettest Aprils in
the last 100 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial of Prominent Iranian Reformist Assassination Suspects Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Iranian revolutionary court on
Tuesday opened trial on 10 suspects accused of involvement in the
failed assassination attempt against Saeed Hajjarian, a close
reformist ally of President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
The trial was presided over by the newly-appointed conservative
judge Hussein Razqandi. Ahmad Hakimipour, who rushed Hajjarian to a
nearby hospital to save his life, also appeared at the court as an
eyewitness, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Hajjarian, deputy chairman of Tehran Municipal Council, was shot
and severely wounded in front of the council building on March 12.
He has regained consciousness after a long coma, but is still
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
Iranian authorities have claimed on several occassions that the
10 suspects have no affiliation to any group or guild or
foreigners, but they had carried out the assassination attempt on
their own and out of personal feelings and motivations.
</P>
<P>
Hakimipour was also temporally detained on April 15 on charge of
having a hand in the assassination, but was released on bail on
April 20.
</P>
<P>
Hakimipour, a reformist member of Tehran Municipal Council,
became a suspect in the assassination case because a letter handed
over to Hajjarian, which prepared the ground for the assassination
attempt, was signed by Hakimipour.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives claimed that the assassination attempt was an
internal dispute of the reformist camp after Hakimipour's arrest.
However, public opinion believed that the attempt was a revenge
against Hajjarian by the conservatives, who still dominate the
country's most sensitive organs.
</P>
<P>
Hajjarian, managing director of the reformist daily Sobh-e
Emrouz (This Morning) and a former deputy intelligence minister,
played an important role in the reformist landslide victory in the
February parliamentary election, which humiliated the powerful
conservatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
