<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- U.N. Middle East special envoy Terje Larsen of Norway is due
to meet with senior Israeli officials in Jerusalem on Tuesday to
discuss Israel's plans to pull the Israeli troops out of south
Lebanon by July.
</P>
<P>
Government sources confirmed that Larsen will meet with National
Security Adviser Danny Yatom and probably Foreign Minister David
Levy. No meeting with Prime Minister Ehud Barak is planned,
although Larsen did hold impromptu talks with him on a previous
visit to Israel a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the Prime Minister's Office said Larsen's latest
visit to the region is apparently part of the U.N.'s preparations
for the proposed Israel Defense Forces (IDF) pullout. This was
confirmed by U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) official
Daljeet Bagga.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's General Security Service (Shin Bet) has recommended
to Prime Minister Ehud Barak that all prisoners identified with the
Fatah organization and with other groups that are part of the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) be released as part of the
negotiations with the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation includes prisoners convicted of murdering or
wounding Israelis. Apart from isolated cases, Israel has so far
refrained from releasing Palestinian prisoners "with Israeli blood
on their hands" within the framework of the Oslo process.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian police and Israeli border police scuffled Monday
afternoon near the Kfar Darom settlement in the Gaza Strip, only
stopped when Israel Defense Forces and PNA liaison officials came
to end the brawl.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians have complained for some time that the Jewish
settlement's sewage drains ran near Palestinian houses, which
residents said stank and attracted harmful insects.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of local Arab residents, apparently supported by PNA
security officials, stated work to block the settlement's sewage
pipe. Israeli border police demanded that the unauthorized pipe-
obstruction work stop - and tussling then broke out, involving
curses, shoving and blows.
</P>
<P>
IDF sources estimate that Palestinians and Israelis have been
trying to create facts on the ground prior to the permanent status
talks.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Bank of Israel Governor David Klein surprised economists on
Monday by reducing the key lending rate by 0.3 percentage points to
9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The reduction, the sixth in a row, was made possible by the very
low inflationary environment and the sustained strength of the
local currency, sources in the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
The move was seen as a surprise because of the combination of
increased interest rates in the U.S. and the volatility of the
world's financial markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
