<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Couple Escaping Gunmen Abduction in Malaysia Suffer Shock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
American-born James Murphy, 50, and his wife Mary, 49, who have
been living in Australia for two years, were staying at a
Malaysian diving resort when a group of heavily armed masked
gunmen attacked.
</P>
<P>
About 20 people, including foreign tourists, were captured from
Sipadan Island off eastern Malaysia and taken away on fishing
boats, apparently to the Philippines waters.
</P>
<P>
But the Murphys managed a bold escape after Mrs. Murphy
complained she could not swim and her husband refused to leave
without her.
</P>
<P>
Their son James, 26, said they had managed to run into the
jungle, and hid for 10 to 12 hours before the authorities arrived.
</P>
<P>
Once found, they returned to Malaysia's capital Kuala Lumpur to
recover from the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
The couple, originally from Rochester, New York, have kept in
regular contact with their three children, and told James they
expected to return to Australia later this week or early next week.
</P>
<P>
"They were scared, but now they're doing much better," James
said.
</P>
<P>
"Mum says she has lots of bites on her legs, after waiting in
the jungle for so long," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Murphy, who celebrated his 50th birthday in March, is a
technologies manager for Eastman Kodak in Sydney, and is involved
in preparations for the Sydney Olympic Games.  His wife does
volunteer work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
