<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Wants WTO to Ensure Benefits to Developing  Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia wants the World
Trade Organization (WTO)'s existing rules and agreements to be
reviewed and amended, where appropriate, to ensure developing
countries benefit from trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
"WTO must strive to bring more equitable benefits to developing
countries," Primary Industries Ministry Secretary General Harun
Siraj said Tuesday at the conference here on "International
Economic and Trade Liberalization: Challenges to Muslim Countries".
</P>
<P>
Developing countries must be given adequate time to understand
the issues and its implications before any new negotiation could
be considered, he said when presenting "Malaysia's Response To The
New Trade Agenda" at the conference.
</P>
<P>
He said "The consensus approach in the WTO need to be upheld
while the greater transparency in the WTO decision-making process
is needed towards engaging members, especially developing
countries."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the WTO director general has a crucial role in
ensuring that the interest and views of all members, particularly
developing countries, are taken into account when formulating the
WTO work program.
</P>
<P>
The WTO's work program must be realistic and manageable and
should not be overloaded, he said, adding contentious issues such
as trade facilitation, investment, competition policy, labour and
environment,on which no consensus was reached should not be
included.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia was prepared to join the emerging consensus to
include negotiations on market access for non-agriculture products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
