<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Carrier Discovered Through Pre-marriage Checkup in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- An unidentified young woman in
Beijing has become the first person in the Chinese capital to test
positive for the HIV virus during a routine pre-marriage medical
check-up, the Beijing Morning Newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted sources with the Beijing Birth Control
Institute as saying the woman, a Beijing resident, was found to be
HIV-positive, and was told to postpone her marriage application.
</P>
<P>
The girl was then sent to a local venereal disease treatment
center for another medical checkup, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the institute show the incidence of venereal
diseases among those undergoing the required pre-marriage physical
checkup reached 6.7 per 10,000 in 1999, almost double the number
in 1998, or 3.6 per 10,000, it said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the venereal diseases reported in the group are pointed
cindyloma (verruca acuminata) and syphilis.
</P>
<P>
About 140,000 to 160,000 adults register for marriage each year
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, China has 17,316 registered AIDS
carriers, 677 of which were women.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
