<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Beefs up Patrol on Malaysian Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 25, (Xinhua) -- The Armed Forces of the
Philippines(AFP) said Tuesday that it has beefed up joint border
patrol to track down the kidnappers of some 20 foreigners taken
last Sunday night at Sipadan island, Sabah, Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Ernesto De Guzman, AFP Southern Command chief of staff said in
a statement that they have sent additional troops on board
Philippine Navy gunboats to help the Malaysian Royal Navy in their
search and rescue operation to retrieve the 20 kidnapped victims.
</P>
<P>
The 20 foreigners were believed kidnapped by at least eight
armed Filipinos believed also to be symphatizers of the extremist
Abu Sayyaf group operating in the southern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
De Guzman said a team from the Philippine Air Force have also
been dispatched to the area to conduct surveillance patrol in the
islets and islands of the provinces of Tawi-Tawi and Sulu.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Malaysian government to the Southcom
headquarters in Zamboanga city said the 20 foreigners were
composed of five Malaysian government officials, a Malaysian
police, four beach workers while the 10 are of different
nationalities.
</P>
<P>
Sipadan island is a known diving area for foreign visitors who
would like to enjoy the natural corals in the area.
</P>
<P>
It was not confirmed yet whether the Filipino abductors brought
their captives to the southern Philippines but officials said they
could be simple sea pirates operating between the Malaysian-
Philippine border.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine and Malaysia government have signed few years
back a joint border patrol agreement to maintain security in the
border area.
</P>
<P>
No demands from the abductors have yet been reported by the
Philippine authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Kills 72 Children Daily in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Seventy-two children under the
age of five years die of malaria daily in Kenya, a malaria expert
has said.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper Tuesday quoted Dr Beth Rapuoda as
saying " with 107 per 1,000 children aged below five dying of
malaria annually, the disease places a heavy burden on the health
system."
</P>
<P>
Rapuoda said the disease accounts for 30 percent of all
out-patient cases, 19 percent of all admissions and 5.1 percent of
whom die.
</P>
<P>
Malaria ranks the second killer disease in Kenya after AIDS.
The malaria endemic areas are mainly in southwestern Kenya
including Narok, Kisii, Kericho, Nandi, Kilifi districts among
others.
</P>
<P>
The anticipated perennial outbreak of malaria is possible in
parts of Nyanza, Rift Valley and Western provinces due to the
start of the long rain season between March and June.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Nyanza Provincial Medical Officer Ambrose Misore
said of 400 patients at the Kisii Hospital, between 80 to 90 were
malaria victims.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said that in Kisii District alone, 121 people
died of the disease and over 12,000 others were affected by the
epidemic this year.
</P>
<P>
To prevent and treat the disease, Kenya's Health Ministry had
allocated 320 million shillings (around 4.2 million U.S. dollars)
for anti-malaria drugs this financial year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
