<HEADLINE> Philippine Firm Wins Concession to Run Dar Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A Philippine firm has won a
10-year concession to operate and manage the Dar es Salaam
container terminal, the African newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine port operator International Container Terminal
Services Inc. (ICTSI), its subsidiary ICTSI International Holdings
Corp. and Tanzanian firm Vertex Financial Services are to sign the
contract with the Tanzanian government on May 5, the Filipino firm
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The group is to take over operations in August.
</P>
<P>
The consortium, called the Tanzania International Container
Terminal Services Ltd., submitted the highest bid and is expected
to spend 6.5 million U.S. dollars over the 10-year concession to
refurbish, add new equipment and introduce a computer system for
the dilapidated port, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Dar es Salaam container terminal is one of the major marine
ports on the Indian Ocean coast operated by the Tanzania Harbors
Authority (THA). It serves both Tanzania and the neighboring
landlocked countries like Zambia, Rwanda, Burundi, the Democratic
Republic of the Congo, Uganda and Malawi.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of the government's plan to privatize the
Tanzania Harbors Authority, added the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
