<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nikkei Stock Index Declines in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The benchmark Nikkei index fell
sharply in Tokyo Tuesday, with issues newly added to the index
continuing to face profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 207.82 points, or 1.12
percent, from Monday's close to end at 18,272.33.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX) which covers
all First Section issues, however, added 4.47 points, or 0.27
percent, to 1,665.28, rising for the sixth straight trading day.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 537.36 million
shares from Monday's 657.54 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
New Nikkei components faced selling after gaining in the
morning session, traders said, adding that many of the 30 new
issues on the key market gauge will be top-heavy for the rest of
the week after drawing active buying last week.
</P>
<P>
Monday's plunge in New York's technology-heavy NASDAQ composite
index was another factor weighing on Tokyo share prices, they said.
</P>
<P>
Export-oriented technology issues in Tokyo were generally lower,
reflecting the weakness in the NASDAQ.
</P>
<P>
Real estate firms were the biggest winners, rising 4.42 percent
as a group, while banks, electric power and gas firms, and
wholesalers also gained.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers narrowly
surpassed gainers 659 to 617, while 112 issues ended unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
