<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Grain Acreage to Drop Five Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China's grain acreage is expected
to drop by five percent this year from a year earlier, while that
of oil-bearing crops will jump about 10 percent, according to a
recent survey by the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Of the total grain acreage, the area of land planted with
summer wheat is expected to decline by six percent, and that of
low-yield, poor quality wheat south of the Yangtze River will see
the biggest cut. Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Hubei, Anhui, Sichuan and
other major grain producing provinces in this region account for
70 percent of the total drop in the grain acreage.
</P>
<P>
The acreage of quality wheat for special purposes has expanded
at the same time, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The acreage of summer oil-bearing crops reached a record high
this year, with central China's Hubei and Hunan provinces as well
as eastern Jiangsu Province enjoying the most growth. In Hunan,
the acreage of quality oil-bearing crops now exceeds 667,000
hectares.
</P>
<P>
The survey says that summer grain seedlings are growing well in
general, however, the drought in north China and the continuous
rain in some areas south of the Yangtze River and in southwest
China have affected wheat growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Close 103 Small Steelworks This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China will close its 225 small
steelworks in the next few years, and has set this year's target
at 103, according to the State Administration of Metallurgical
Industry(SAMI).
</P>
<P>
Both small steelworks and large steel plants with out-dated
steel production capacity of 4.5 million tons will be eliminated
this year.
</P>
<P>
Pu Haiqing, director of SAMI, said here today that closing the
small steelworks and cutting out-dated production capacity will
help improve steel quality, prevent shoddy construction, protect
the environment, save energy, and promote the sustainable growth
of China's national economy.
</P>
<P>
Out of the current 290 steelworks in China, the 225 small mills
account for only 7.5 percent of total production. These mills are
generally heavy polluters and high energy consumers, and their
products are of low standard.
</P>
<P>
Shi Wanpeng, deputy director of the State Economic and Trade
Commission(SETC), noted that closing small steelworks is not
equivalent to cutting production, but is instrumental to the
restructuring of the industry and improvement of the steel
products.
</P>
<P>
"It is also prompted by strong competition in the global steel
market as China is seeking entry to the World Trade Organization(
WTO)," Shi said.
</P>
<P>
China's energy and finance sectors will also join this move by
limiting supplies of fuel, power, and loans to those soon-to-be-
closed small mills, and licenses of some steelworks will be
revoked by the authorities.
</P>
<P>
China's first quarter steel production reached 29.8 million
tons, up 3.2 percent on an annual basis, showing a slowing down to
a great extent.
</P>
<P>
As the world's largest steel producer, China turned out 124.3
million tons of steel in 1999. Production is expected to be about
110 million tons this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Cable Network in Asia Pacific to Be Built </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua)-- China Telecom and other 25
telecommunication companies in the Asia Pacific Region has signed
an agreement to build the first self-healing high bandwidth
optical fiber submarine cable system in the region.
</P>
<P>
The cable, known as the Asian Pacific Cable Network 2, will
cost about one billion US dollars and is expected to carry
commercial traffic by the end of September 2001, according to
China Telecom here today.
</P>
<P>
Upon its completion, the 19,000 km-long cable system will
connect eight countries and regions in the Asia Pacific Region.
Besides serving the region, the cable system will also provide
seamless interconnection with other major trans-oceanic cable
networks providing connection to the USA, European countries,
Australia and other parts of Asia.
</P>
<P>
The cable system is designed to use state-of-the-art Dense
Wavelength Division Multiplexing technology to provide upgradable,
future-proof transmission facilities that support the Internet and
e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the cable system will have a "self-healing ring
configuration" with four fiber-optic pairs, with greater network
resilience and route diversity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
