<HEADLINE> Kenya to Introduce Tough Traffic Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A tough traffic bill will be
submitted to Kenya's parliament within two weeks to amend the
current law, Kenya's Attorney-General Amos Wako has said.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Times Tuesday quoted Wako as saying that the traffic
amendment act would impose harsh penalties on offenders since the
cases of road accidents had reached an alarming rate.
</P>
<P>
In the last one month, more than 150 people were killed by road
 accidents in the east African country due to overload, overspeed
or reckless overtaking.
</P>
<P>
The bill had already been approved by the cabinet, Wako said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Information, Transport and Communications Minister
Musalia Mudavadi said that current traffic laws were too lenient.
</P>
<P>
Musalia revealed that the amendments would also seek to install
speed devices in buses to curb speeding and punish people who
board vehicles already full to capacity.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the amendments were expected to serve as
a deterrent to check indisciplined drivers and restore passengers'
confidence. 
