<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Go Away for Lack of Good Stocks: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The major reason for foreign
investors to refrain from investing in Thai stocks is the absence
of good quality securities, particularly technology stocks, a
survey report disclosed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Other reasons include insufficient market liquidity and a lack
of confidence in the listed companies, said a survey report
released by the Securities and Exchange Commission of Thailand (
SEC).
</P>
<P>
According to the survey respondents, mainly local and foreign
securities companies, there are many reasons for the lack of high
quality securities in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
One reason is that viable companies have chosen not to be
listed on the stock exchange and another is that the listed
companies want to be delisted because they no longer see the
benefits of remaining on the exchange.
</P>
<P>
In addition, disclosure requirements for listed companies are
seen as a curb on their competitiveness and so they have opted to
remain unlisted.
</P>
<P>
To increase the amount of good quality stocks, the survey
respondents recommended that the Thai stock market should provide
incentives for companies to become listed.
</P>
<P>
Another way to attract foreign investors is for the Thai stock
market to improve the processes and procedures for buying and
selling stocks,the survey respondents said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Become Tesco's Asian Hub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Buoyed by its successful hyper-
market business in Thailand, the British retailing giant Tesco Plc.
said the country will be its top site in Asia for investment, the
Bangkok Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Thailand would be the business development center for discount
stores in the region, Tesco Chairman John Gardiner was quoted as
saying Monday in Bangkok at the opening of the 20th Tesco-Lotus
store in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"Everything we learn from Thailand will benefit Tesco's
operations in other countries worldwide," Gardiner said.
</P>
<P>
The company is already applying some experience from Tesco-
Lotus Thailand in terms of marketing, space management and product
management to Tesco stores in South Korea and Britain, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand has the highest potential among Tesco operations
worldwide in terms of non-food operation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tesco has assigned executives of its food business to work with
Thai farmers to introduce new technology to increase crop yields.
They will also work on developing worldwide standards and
increasing the competitiveness of food products.
</P>
<P>
Work is also being done on the distribution-supply chain for
fresh and processed foods.
</P>
<P>
Tesco has also set up a purchasing center in Thailand to source
products such as apparel and distribute them to other purchasing
centers abroad including Central Europe and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Thailand, the company is developing businesses
in South Korea and Taiwan and is considering China's mainland and
other places as possible investment destinations.
</P>
<P>
So far, the company has invested 360 million British pounds (
540 million U.S. dollars) in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 2003, Tesco's investment in Thailand will total
600 million pounds (900 million dollars) and it will have 40
stores in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
