<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 04:30 GMT, April 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Worldwide PC market expanded by a big margin in
the first quarter of 2000 as compared with a year ago, according
to preliminary estimates released Monday by two U.S. market
research firms.
</P>
<P>
International Data Corporation (IDC) reported that worldwide PC
market volume expanded 20 percent year after year, with shipments
totaling 30.4 million units, while Dataquest estimated a 15
percent growth with shipments surpassing 29.9 million units.
</P>
<P>
Both firms listed strong growth in Asia-Pacific and Japan as
the leading factor behind the worldwide market expansion. (World-
PC Market)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico and Brazil agreed upon a reciprocal
tariff of 8 percent to bilateral automobile exports, Eduardo Solis,
head of Mexico's office of trade negotiations with Latin America
announced here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The tariff accord will come into effect when the Latin
American Association of Integration authorizes it in forthcoming
days, Solis said.
</P>
<P>
Under the two-year accord, each of them will export 40,000
vehicles in the first year and 50,000 in the second, he said,
adding the accord includes sedans, pickups and nine-ton cargo
trucks. (Mexico-Brazil-Automobile)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's non-traditional exports reached 1.591
billion U.S. dollars for the first quarter of this year, an 8.5
percent increase over the same period last year, said the Central
Bank Monday.
</P>
<P>
The earnings of non-traditional industrial exports came to 1.
478 billion dollars, while farming, forest and fishing sector
sales amounted to 97.4 million dollars, said the bank. (Chile-
Export
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand is entering a post-crisis growth path, as
nearly all sectors in the economy have recovered and will be able
to cope with even changing external factors, a top official said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi was quoted by the official Thai News Agency as saying
that after assessing the overall economic prospects and conditions
in local financial and foreign exchange markets, the government
found that nearly all sectors had recovered. (Thailand-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB) said Tuesday that it
has approved a 29.8 million-U.S.-dollar project in East Timor to
undertake emergency road repairs, expand Dili port facilities and
restore electricity.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said in a press release that the Emergency
Infrastructure Rehabilitation Project will facilitate the delivery
of food and agricultural supplies, the resettlement of displaced
persons and the movement of the U.N. Peacekeeping Forces.
</P>
<P>
The project will also support financial management of East
Timor's power sector and capacity building of transport sector
institutions. (Philippines-ADB-East Timor) 
</P>
