<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Faces Difficulties in Hosting NAM Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The proposed summit of the Non-
Aligned Movement (NAM) due to be held in Dhaka next year looks
uncertain as the huge expenditure required for massive
preparations appears to be absent, The New Nation newspaper
reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a diplomatic source as saying the present
hotels and apartments are not enough for the visiting heads of
government and guests.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh now burdened with a sliding economy is facing
difficulties in hosting such an event, which would cost more than
10 billion taka (200 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The transport system at the government level for the movement
of the delegations of the 115 NAM member countries would also be a
serious issue, the source said.
</P>
<P>
The movement of the visiting heads of state or government along
with the ministers would require special cars to be imported for
their use during the three-day summit.
</P>
<P>
Another vitally important factor would be the issue of security
for all the VIPs. It would be viewed in the context of the recent
mismanagement during the visit of U.S. President Bill Clinton to
Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
On security ground, the U.S. president had to drop his
scheduled program to a nearby village to see the rural development.
</P>
<P>
The source pointed out that cancellation of the scheduled
program caused serious concern both at home and abroad and it
would have a lingering impact on all future programs of foreign
dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
Hosting the NAM summit next year would also be difficult as
Bangladesh would face a hectic campaign for the coming general
election due next year. Both the ruling party and the opposition
parties would engage themselves for the electioneering, paying
little attention to the coming NAM summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
