<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Aims to Halt Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government is
aiming to reduce the country's population growth to zero as the
current 1-percent annual increase costs too much, a U.N.-sponsored
program said in its latest newsletter.
</P>
<P>
"The government spends around 5 percent of gross national
product on health," said the Reproductive Health Initiative (RHI),
a joint program launched in 1997 by the U.N. Population Fund in
association with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka, with a population of 19 million, was included as the
seventh country to receive funding under the RHI program.
</P>
<P>
The other countries included in the program are Bangladesh with
a growth rate of 1.7 percent, Cambodia 2.3 percent, Laos 2.6
percent,Nepal 2.4 percent, Pakistan 2.8 percent and Vietnam 1.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
The basis for including Sri Lanka to receive funding under the
RHI program was the non-availability of services to young people,
especially the lack of counseling and information, said the
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
It said significant progress had been made by Sri Lanka with a
dramatic decrease in child and infant mortality from 130 per 1,000
live births in 1960 to 18 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka also compares favorably with other countries in
maintaining a low fertility rate with the use of contraceptives,
said the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
Over 60 percent of the population use contraceptives compared
with 19 percent in Pakistan and under 50 percent in Bangladesh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0285 </DOCNO>
