<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Economy Recovers in All-Around Way: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is entering a post-
crisis growth path, as nearly all sectors in the economy have
recovered and will be able to cope with even changing external
factors, a top official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi was quoted by the official Thai News Agency as saying
that after assessing the overall economic prospects and conditions
in local financial and foreign exchange markets, the government
found that nearly all sectors had recovered.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after a governmental economic meeting on
Tuesday, at the Bank of Thailand, the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
The production capacity of the automobile and electronic
industries had particularly increased by 70 percent and 120
percent respectively while the baht, the country's currency, has
been satisfactorily stable, Supachai noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the conditions reflected that the Thai economy is now
in a fresh firm position that enables it to cope with even
changing external factors, namely an anticipated increase of U.S.
interest rates soon.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Finance Minister Pisit Lee-Artham also expressed
similar views on Tuesday, saying the overall Thai economy is now
in a better prospect, with improving exports and industrial
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
The only concern now is the deteriorating prices of
agricultural products, affected by conditions in the world market,
which the government is working hard to address, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Lasting Peace: A Dream of N. Irish People  (By Huang Xingwei) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELFAST, Northern Ireland, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Belfast, the
capital of Northern Ireland, a name synonymous with bombs and
sectarianism. But once you are in the city, you will see another
side.
</P>
<P>
For first-time visitors to Belfast, they might be pleasantly
surprised. It is quite difficult to see a policeman or an armored
patrol car in the street, or to find shopping malls packed with
customers rushing to buy Easter gifts. The seaside city is quite
different from what they have seen or heard about from newspapers,
television or radio.
</P>
<P>
In the evening, the city's bars, clubs and restaurants,
especially in the city center, are crammed to overflowing. It
seems that a generation deprived of a night life by a three-decade-
long armed conflict has decided to have a permanent party while it
has the chance.
</P>
<P>
Inside the 200-year-old Crown Liquor Saloon, located at Great
Victoria Street, a Catholic named Hugh told Xinhua that in Belfast
people rarely ask you whether you are a Catholic or a Protestant.
</P>
<P>
"I have many Protestant friends. We get along with each other
quite well despite our different political views. Only time will
tell you that the people's desire to live a normal life here
outweighs the minority's needs to cling to the hatreds and past,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The armed conflicts, which started in 1969, between the
Protestants and Catholics in Northern Ireland have claimed 3,600
lives in the past 30 years, and brought constant turmoil to
Belfast, a city with a population of 300,000.
</P>
<P>
On April 10, 1998, the conflicting parties signed the historic
Good Friday peace agreement in Belfast, providing the Northern
Irish people with a new possibility to see the "dawn of peace."
</P>
<P>
In Northern Ireland, the number of tourists is the barometer of
public security. Some 1.64 million people visited Northern Ireland
in 1999, contributing 255 million pounds (408 million U.S. dollars
to its revenue, an 11-percent increase over the previous year,
Northern Ireland Tourist Board statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the 1990s, Northern Ireland enjoyed the fastest
economic growth of any region in the United Kingdom, John Murrary
from the Northern Ireland Industrial Development told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Between 1990 and 1995, Northern Ireland's GDP grew by 11.6
percent in real terms compared with 5.3 percent for Great Britain
as a whole. And in recent years, foreign investment in software,
telecommunications and e-commerce has been increasing dramatically,
he said.
</P>
<P>
On Easter Sunday, thousands of Catholics held the annual mass
rally in West Belfast to commemorate the 1916 Easter Rising in
which thousands of Catholics died in the independence-seeking
uprising against Britain. But Sinn Fein, the political wing of the
Irish Republican Army (IRA), announced no new initiatives at the
commemorations.
</P>
<P>
The parade indicated that hundreds of years of hatred between
the Catholics and Protestants could not possibly melt like ice in
a short time, and the national reconciliation would be a long and
tortuous process.
</P>
<P>
In February, the British government suspended the Northern
Irish assembly as the IRA showed no signs of decommissioning,
raising fears of the return of violence in the province.
</P>
<P>
But John Murrary was quite optimistic about the future. "The
Northern Irish people are anxious for a lasting peace. Once the
Northern Irish assembly is restored and the paramilitary
organizations hand over their arms, by then you could discover a
new Northern Ireland with changes every day," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
