<HEADLINE> Six Children Wounded in Washington Shooting (Update with more details) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Six children were wounded as
two feuding groups of youths exchanged gunfire at the National Zoo
in Washington Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Brian Lee, spokesman for the District of Columbia Fire and
Emergency Medical Services, said one boy suffered serious wounds
to the head. The other victims ranged in age on 11-16 and most
were listed in critical or serious condition.
</P>
<P>
Police helicopters hovered over the zoo after the shooting as
authorities sought a gunman.
</P>
<P>
At the time of the shooting, shortly after 6 p.m. local time,
the zoo, a unit of the Smithsonian Institution, was playing host
to an "African-American Family Day," featuring live music
performances, storytellers, dancers and African drummers.
</P>
<P>
At least two of the victims were shot at the zoo's visitors
center and one was shot at the zoo entrance on Connecticut Avenue,
a main thoroughfare in the northwest section of the U.S. capital.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said the shooting occurred when a bottle was thrown
from one group of youths at another. A piece of glass struck a
young woman in the face, and then shots rang out, they added.
</P>
<P>
The National Zoo is one of the most visited sites in Washington,
drawing 3 million local residents and visiting tourists each year.
</P>
<P>
Police said no arrests had been made. 
</P>
</TEXT>
