<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Atlantis Grounding Not to Delay Olympic Torch Relay: SOCOG  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The grounding of a space shuttle
with the Sydney Olympic torch on board would not affect the timing
of the 2000 Games torch relay, organisers said Tuesday in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Strong cross-winds at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida, the
United States, prevented the launch of the flight carrying the
Olympic torch into space Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The boomerang-shaped torch and an Olympic flag are among cargo
stowed inside the space shuttle Atlantis, which was scheduled to
leave with a crew of seven on a mission to repair the
international space station before strong winds grounded the
flight minutes before take-off.
</P>
<P>
But a spokesman of the Sydney Organising Committee for the
Olympic Games (SOCOG) said the shuttle delay would not interfere
with the schedule for the Olympic torch relay.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a setback and it's not going to delay the start of
the relay," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"SOCOG remains confident that the torch will be in space in
time to promote the start of the Sydney 2000 torch relay," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic flame will leave Olympia in Greece in May 2000 and
travel for almost five months before it lights the cauldron at
Homebush stadium on September 15, 2000.
</P>
<P>
SOCOG said the torch was a specially designed for space travel.
</P>
<P>
"Because of limited space on board the shuttle, the torch was
designed so that it can be dismantled and taken into space," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
When the flight begins, the torch will orbit the earth about 15
times a day and will travel about 6.5 million kilometers through
space.
</P>
<P>
As well as going into space, the torch is also set to go under
water, with part of the torch relay to take in the Great Barrier
Reef, off the Queensland coast in northeast Australia.
</P>
<P>
"It will be the most travelled and transported torch in Olympic
history," the SOCOG spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
