<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half of U.S. Small Businesses Establish Home Page </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-two percent of small
businesses in the United States established a home page in 1999,
and the number is expected to rise to over 70 percent by 2003,
according to a report released Monday.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, 2.1 million U.S. small businesses with fewer than 100
employees had a home page or website, and the number will increase
30 percent to 2.7 million in 2000, said the report from market
research firm International Data Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
"Once confined by geographical constraints, small businesses in
the United States are now leveraging the Internet to expand beyond
local boundaries," the report said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to using information on the Web, small businesses
are recognizing the benefit of promoting themselves via the Web.
But IDC estimated that almost 13 percent of U.S. small businesses
have yet to invest in a PC.
</P>
<P>
At this point, IDC said, e-commerce presents the most
significant growth opportunity for a wide range of U.S. small
businesses. The number of these companies selling goods and
services online will grow from 850,000 at the end of 1999 to 2.9
million in 2003.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet has tremendous reach, and small businesses are
beginning to realize the potential of this channel," said the
report. "By 2003 nearly half of online small businesses will be
selling over the Internet." 
</P>
</TEXT>
