<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Cataract Patients in Shaanxi Restore Eyesight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Shi Guifang, a female farmer
suffering from cataract for many years, regained her eyesight
after receiving a surgical operation at a mobile medical vehicle
recently.
</P>
<P>
Shi was among the 3,000 beneficiaries of the "Sightfirst China
Act Project" in northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
"Sightfirst China Act" is a blindness prevention and treatment
project, the largest of its kind in the world, being developed
with the combined efforts of China and the Lions Club
International.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi has 140,000 cataract patients, many of whom can restore
their eyesight after operation. However, 80 percent of the
patients live in rural areas where competent doctors and up-to-
date medical equipment are not available.
</P>
<P>
The Shaanxi Provincial Government launched an eyesight
restoration program in cooperation with the Hong Kong Society for
the Blind in 1996. Key hospitals in Shaanxi have dispatched
renowned experts to work on the mobile medical vehicle.
</P>
<P>
Over the past four years, the mobile medical vehicle has
traversed 57 rural counties with a total length of 30,000 km and
conducted 3,000 cataract sight-restoring surgeries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
