<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adamant in Fighting Erosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China intends to bring 50,000
square kilometers of land that have suffered erosion back into use
and curb additional soil erosion, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Zhai Haohui, vice-minister of water resources, urged local
governments at various levels to intensify their erosion-control
efforts this year.
</P>
<P>
Soil erosion would worsen in the western region with large-
scale construction of highways, railways, mining and exploitation
of water resources if effective measures and strict monitoring are
not taken, Zhai warned.
</P>
<P>
Soil erosion plagues more than one-third of the country, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, the state has spent three billion yuan (
361 million US dollars) on a series of key erosion-control
projects upstream of the Yangtze River and on the Loess Plateau
along the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
So far, China has protected 830,000 square kilometers of land
suffering from water shortages and soil erosion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
