<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Persons Responsible for Major Coal Mine Accident Dealt With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Twelve persons who were found
responsible for a major coal mine accident last January in the
city of Xuzhou in east China's Jiangsu Province, were dealt with
recently according to law.
</P>
<P>
On January 11, the Dahuangshan Coal Mine under the Xuzhou
Mining Administration was inundated by underground water, and 63
workers became trapped 400 to 500 meters underground, 22 of whom
were later killed. Direct economic losses from the accident were
estimated at 2.78 million yuan (about 334,939 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
An group of investigators made up of provincial labor bureau,
the coal mine administrative office, and the public security
bureau reached the conclusion based on extensive investigations
that the tragedy was caused by inaccurate hydrological data and
dereliction of duty.
</P>
<P>
Among the 12 who were punished, Zhang Jun, a coal mine
technician, was found responsible for failing to report head-on
water discharging signs in time, which led to a delay in the
withdrawal of miners working underground, and eventually led to
the tragedy. Zhang has been handed over to a local judicial
department for holding criminal responsibility in the accident.
</P>
<P>
Pei Daoqi and Liu Maode, two workers with the geological
section of the Dahuangshan Coal Mine, were found responsible for
failing to provide accurate hydrological data. Pei was expelled
from the coal mine, and Liu was given a disciplinary sanction.
</P>
<P>
The coal mine, with 5,000 workers, has been shut down and
production has ceased. All the workers will be shifted elsewhere,
and arrangements for their future work are being carried out, said
local sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
