<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wilkens Resigns as Atlanta Hawks Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Lenny Wilkens, who holds the
record for most victories by an NBA coach, resigned from his post
with the Atlanta Hawks on Monday after enduring the worst season
of his 27-year coaching career.
</P>
<P>
The Hawks announced the resignation of the Hall of Fame coach
at an afternoon news conference, saying they were seeking a
younger coach to direct a rebuilding team.
</P>
<P>
The 62-year-old Wilkens had two years remaining on his Hawks
contract.
</P>
<P>
The Hawks finished the 1999-2000 campaign with a miserable 28-
54 record, their worst season since the club moved to Atlanta in
1968.
</P>
<P>
Wilkens, who coached Seattle to an NBA championship in 1979,
owns a career coaching record of 1,179-981, including a 310-232
record in seven years with the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
Wilkens, who has also coached Portland and Cleveland, was
elected to the Basketball Hall of Fame as a player and a coach,
making him the only double inductee from the NBA.
</P>
<P>
He was voted to the list of the NBA's 50 Greatest Players in
1996 and later was named one of the NBA's 10 Greatest Coaches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
