<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nature Reserve To Protect Egrets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A nature reserve to protect
egrets has been created in Shibanya Village in the Banan District
of southwest China's Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
The local government has invested 100,000 yuan (12,048 U.S.
dollars) for the An Lan Egret Bird Nature Reserve, which is
expected to become an ecological tourist zone within three years,
according to the district's deputy director Lu Wei.
</P>
<P>
Unlike other nature reserves, this one was built on the basis
of a bird park initiated by local farmers.
</P>
<P>
The number of wild egrets in the village has increased from
about 100 eight years ago to the present 30,000.
</P>
<P>
An official from the local forestry department attributes this
achievement to 59-year-old farmer Wen Shihua, who launched a bird
protection drive eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
Wen's determination to save the birds resulted in the expansion
of the village's bird habitat area to over 50 mu (3.3 hectares).
</P>
<P>
Beginning last year, the local government has been allocating a
certain fund each year to compensate 14 households whose bamboo
forests -- their main source of income -- have become bird havens.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing now has three nature reserves for the protection of
egrets and 260 other bird species.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
