<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus against Direct EU Funding of Turkish Cypriot Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Any bicommunal projects and any
funds for such projects will have to have the consent of Cyprus
government, government spokesman Michalis Papapetrou said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also stressed that funding must not, directly or
indirectly, give rise to recognition of the Turkish Cypriot regime
in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou made the remarks in response to press reports that
European Union (EU) funds will find their way to the Turkish
Cypriot community via means that could be tantamount to recognition
of the northern regime of the island.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou said work is already underway to set up an office in
Brussels of non-governmental organizations and to contribute to the
sewerage system of wider Nicosia, including the northern part
controlled by Turkish Cypriots and the southern part dominated by
Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
"All projects that may materialize and all funds to be allocated
will go ahead with the consent of the Republic of Cyprus,"
Papapetrou said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island after a failed coup seeking union with
Athens.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a republic in
northern Cyprus in 1983 which is recognized only by Turkey, against
the internationally acknowledged Republic of Cyprus dominated by
the Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou explained that EU funds are allocated to the Planning
Bureau of Cyprus government and whenever the Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash has refused to receive funds for the Turkish Cypriot
community, these were placed in the Bureau's account at the Central
Bank for safe-keeping and have remained unused.
</P>
<P>
The EU has repeatedly said it negotiates with governments and
not entities or regimes. Denktash, in his bid to gain international
recognition of his breakaway entity, declines any funds coming
through the government of Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Supports Peaceful Solution to Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- An Australian minister expressed
the hope here Tuesday that a lasting and workable peaceful solution
will be found to the Cyprus issue, the Cyprus News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Australian Federal Minister of Justice and Customs, Senator
Amanda Vanstone, arrived here Monday night for a brief visit to
meet with men and women serving in the Australian Federal Police
Contingent with the U.N. peace-keeping force in Cyprus (UNFICYP).
</P>
<P>
The Australian police contingent numbers 20 persons and has been
on the island for the past 36 years since the island was divided
following the invasion of Turkish troops in the wake of a pro-
Greece coup.
</P>
<P>
Vanstone attended an Australian police function Tuesday morning
at UNFICYP headquarters and later met with Cyprus Minister of
Justice and Public Order Nicos Koshis.
</P>
<P>
The Australian minister praised Cyprus for its effort to curb
money laundering and combat drug trafficking, which she said are
international crimes that do not recognize borders and therefore
need an extraordinary degree of international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Vanstone is due to leave Wednesday morning.  
</P>
</TEXT>
