<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Ministry Frowns at Closure of Reformist Papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Ministry of Culture and
Islamic Guidance on Tuesday said the closure of reformist papers by
the conservative-controlled judiciary would damage the atmosphere
of press freedom in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, led by press freedom advocator Ataollah
Mohajerani, issued an official communique urging government
branches to avoid taking any measures that might restrict the
constitutional freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
As constitutional supervisor over publications in the country,
the ministry also called on different political camps to create a
healthy press environment in stead of stigmatizing each other, the
official IRNA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Refuting allegations that reformist papers are engaged in "mass
manipulation" and catering to the readers, the ministry hinted that
this is also the practice of the conservative press.
</P>
<P>
When necessary, the ministry would publish the result of its
investigations, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
The judiciary has ordered the closure of 13 reformist dailies
and periodicals in the past two days, accusing them of violating
Islamic sanctities and principles.
</P>
<P>
The move was meant to curb the growing reformist movement
fostered by President Mohammed Khatami, whose allies won an
overwhelming victory over their conservative opponents in
February's parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
The closure of papers was condemned by many, including the
Association of Journalists and the Islamic Commission of Human
Rights.
University students from major cities took to the streets on
Tuesday to protest the closure and "defend the freedom of speech,"
IRNA reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Protests Flag-Burning Incidents in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Turkey on Tuesday protested against
the burning of Turkish national flags by Armenians in front of its
diplomatic premises in Greece one day ago, the Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Foreign Ministry early Tuesday summoned Danae
Koumanakou, charge d'affaires of the Greek Embassy in Ankara, over
the incidents and demanded that the Greek government take necessary
measures to prevent the repetition of similar incidents.
</P>
<P>
Some 100-150 Armenians staged a demonstration in front of the
Turkish Embassy in Athens on Monday and burned the Turkish national
flags in protest against the alleged genocide of Armenians by the
Ottoman Empire about 80 years ago.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, nearly 200 Armenians also burnt Turkish flags
in front of the Turkish Consulate General in the northern Greek
province of Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Foreign Ministry issued a statement Tuesday condemning
the incidents.
</P>
<P>
"We consider all attacks targeting the flag, which is a national
symbol of every country, as unacceptable. We condemn yesterday's
demonstrations," said the statement signed by Foreign Ministry
spokesman Panos Beglitis.
</P>
<P>
Armenians claim that 1.5 million Armenians were killed between
1915 and 1923 by the then Turkish Ottoman Empire as part of a
genocidal campaign aimed to drive the Armenian population out of
what now is eastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey maintains that there was no such systematic slaughter and
that many Armenians fled the country of their own choice due to war
and civil unrest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sezer Enjoys Support of Turkish Parties for Presidency by Xing Guoxin and Huai Chengbo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Turkish
Constitutional Court Ahmet Necdet Sezer, who was chosen as the
presidential candidate by leaders of the three ruling parties, has
garnered favor of various parties on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tansu Ciller, the main opposition True Path Party (DYP) leader,
hailed Sezer as "a worthy candidate for presidency with his honest
and reliable character" at her party's parliamentary group meeting
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
DYP deputies who attended the meeting also expressed their
support for Sezer, but they expressed doubts about the sincerity of
the coalition partners, adding that presidential election was a
highly sensitive process that requires a strong political will and
honesty.
</P>
<P>
They recalled that DYP gave support to the constitutional
amendment submitted by the ruling coalition for President Suleyman
Demirel' second term in office, but it failed in votes because of
defections of many deputies from the ruling partner Motherland
Party.
</P>
<P>
Ciller met with Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit on the day to
express her party's doubts on how determined the coalition parties
are in their support for their common candidate.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Recai Kutan, leader of the opposition Virtue
Party (FP), said that his party was ready to support Sezer in the
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting with Ecevit, Kutan said that the FP was in
favor of finalizing the presidential elections before it turns into
a crisis. "We want parties to reach an agreement on the issue to
elect the new president as soon as possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Islamic party leader seemed generous toward Sezer, who
voted for closing the Islamic Welfare Party by the Constitutional
Court in 1998, saying that "we left the past behind and concentrate
on the future."
</P>
<P>
He foresaw that Sezer may be elected as the next president even
in the first round of votes if the coalition partners are sincere
in their agreement, stressing that the FP will give full supports
for him.
</P>
<P>
The Parliamentary Advisory Committee decided to hold the first
round of presidential elections on Thursday. According to the
Constitution, a candidate who gets two-thirds of the votes of all
deputies, or 367 out of the 550-seat parliament, can be elected as
president.
</P>
<P>
The ruling partner Motherland Party (ANAP) Chairman Mesut Yilmaz
called on his deputies to extend "full support" to Sezer after the
presiding judge of the Constitutional Court emerged as the joint
candidate of coalition parties.
</P>
<P>
Addressing his Democratic Left Party (DSP) deputies meeting,
Ecevit said that no one should have any suspicions about Sezer's
loyalty to secular and democratic state of law.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, the leaders of five big political parties in
Parliament reached a consensus on their joint presidential
candidate, who analysts predicted could be elected to office during
the first round of balloting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
