<HEADLINE> Brazil to Increase Exports of Telecommunication Equipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's exports of
telecommunication equipment for Latin America are growing in
relation to exchange devaluation and the increasing demand for new
products in the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister of development, industry and foreign
trade, in this year's first two months, exports of transmitters,
receptors and components registered an increase of 196.7 percent
compared to the same period of last year, reaching 224.3 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Total value of external sales in 1999 was 759.8 million,
increasing by 24.8 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
External sales in the sector are believed to be registering an
even bigger growth, as big manufacturers established in the
country, like Motorola, Ericsson, Siemens, Lucent Technologies and
Samsung, are investing in their production lines or picking up the
fruits of investments made last year.
</P>
<P>
The greater part of these external sales is made up by cellular
telephones. Last year, 1.23 million cellulars were exported.
Infrastructure equipment is also exported, such as radiobase
stations and commuting centrals.
</P>
<P>
Argentina is the main market for telecommunication equipment
made in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, in the first two months of this year,
transmitting and reception equipment was the main article of
exports to Argentina, with sales of 61.9 million dollars and a
growth of 507.8 percent above 1999's same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
