<HEADLINE> U.S. National Safety Council Offers Proposals to Reduce Accidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The wide ranging safety problems are "too big to be solved by
one organization so we formed partnerships with businesses as well
as private and governmental organizations", President of the
National Safety Council Jerry Scannel said.
</P>
<P>
The council estimated that 52,000 people died and 14.5 million
were injured in accidents at home and in public places in the
United States in 1999, up 21 percent since 1992. Falls were the
primary cause of death and injury, especially for older adults.
</P>
<P>
The organization said it is working with the American
Association of Retired Persons to work on preventing falls and
encourage the development of safer home design.
</P>
<P>
An average of 14 people are killed in the workplace every day,
it noted.
</P>
<P>
The council said it is working with the Occupational Safety and
Health Administration and National Institute for Occupational
Safety and Health to expand the use of better safety practices at
work.
</P>
<P>
On the road, where nearly 41,000 deaths occurred in 1999, the
council said it will crusade to get everyone to fasten seat belts.
</P>
