<HEADLINE> Traditional Medicines in Cure of Malaria Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Experts attending the first ever
African Summit on Roll Back Malaria here on Tuesday urged African
leaders to pay greater attention to the roles played by
traditional medicines in preventing and curing the deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
Edugie Abebe, Nigerian medical expert and the summit's manager,
said at a news conference that the registration of traditional
medicine practitioners must be facilitated in order to integrate
them into the "mainstream way" fight against the disease.
</P>
<P>
"So I call on practitioners with remedies that can help in the
eradication of malaria to come and let us carry out research to
verify their claims,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Abebe, the World Health Organization (WHO) has
established a department to coordinate the practice of traditional
medicine.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the conference, David Nabarowo, a WHO
representative, said that the organization is taking pains in
looking into other ways of curing the disease as some kinds of
malaria were becoming resistant to drugs. 
</P>
