<DOCNO> XIE20000425.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Rwandan General Moved to U.N. Genocide Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Augustine Ndindiliyimana,
former Chief of Staff of Rwanda's para-military police forces
(Gendarmerie Nationale), has been transferred from Belgium to a
United Nations court in northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
A statement of the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda
(ICTR) available on Tuesday said that Ndindiliyimana was brought
to the Tribunal's Detention Facility in Arusha last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ndindiliyimana, arrested in the Belgian town of Termonde on
January 29 on the basis of a warrant of arrest issued by the ICTR,
is to answer to 10 counts charging him with genocide, crimes
against humanity and violations of the Geneva Conventions.
</P>
<P>
He is alleged to have participated in planning and preparing
the massacre of about 500,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus in Rwanda
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The 57-year-old former general was also charged with sexual
violence and rape of Tutsi women.
</P>
<P>
"It is further alleged that General Ndindiliyimana and other
senior government and army officials failed to prevent or punish
the perpetrators when elements of the Gendarmerie, the Rwandan
Army and the Interahamwe (militia men) carried out the massacre of
Tutsis," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1943 in Nyaruhengeri commune, Butare Prefecture,
Ndindiliyimana was appointed to the position of Chief of Staff of
the Gendarmerie Nationale on September 2, 1992.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR, created on November 8, 1994 by the United Nations
Security Council Resolution 955, has the mandate to try persons
suspected to be responsible for genocide and other serious
violations of the international humanitarian law committed in the
territory of Rwanda between January 1 and December 31, 1994.
</P>
<P>
It also has the mandate to try Rwandan citizens responsible for
such violations committed in the territory of neighboring states
during the 100- day massacre which claimed more than 500,000
civilians, mostly the ethnic Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR has so far issued 29 indictments against 50
individuals and a total of 44 indicted individuals are in custody,
including several former senior cabinet ministers in the Interim
Government of Rwanda of 1994, former military commanders,
political leaders, journalists and senior businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The five detainees who have already been convicted by the Trial
Chambers of the Tribunal are still held in Arusha, pending outcome
of their appeals, but are kept apart from the other detainees to
whom the presumption of innocence applies.
</P>
<P>
Three of the convicts including former Prime Minister of Rwanda
Jean Kambanda and former Prefect of Kibuye Clement Kayishema have
been sentenced to imprisonment for life.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen Obed Ruzindana and Omar Serushago were sentenced to
25 years and 15 years of imprisonment, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
