<HEADLINE> Canadian Whisky Exports Up 11.6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Whisky exports rose to
622 million Canadian dollars (about 421 million U.S. dollars) in
1999, up 11.6 percent from 557 million Canadian dollars (about 377
million U.S. dollars) in 1998, the Association of Canadian
Distillers announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
That was the 4th consecutive year of growth for the country's
Whisky exports, which are being targeted at a goal of 1 billion
Canadian dollars (about 677 million U.S. dollars) by the year 2005,
said the association.
</P>
<P>
Whisky exports approached the 20 million case mark in 1999,
accounting for nearly 85 percent of the country's production.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been one of the dominant markets for
Canadian Whisky exports. U.S. consumers are buying more Canadian
Whisky than American Bourbon Whisky or Scotch and Irish Whiskies
combined, the association said.
</P>
<P>
Under a multi-year "Enhanced Export Development Program", "the
goal for 2000 is to continue to broaden our export base beyond the
strong American market," said Jan Westcott, president of the
association.
</P>
</TEXT>
