<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls on U.S. Media to Allow Elian Family to Heal Wounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking at an event at the White House, Clinton also praised
Attorney General Janet Reno for the raid that took Elian from his
relatives in Miami Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Now that they have been safely reunited, I believe it is time
for all of us, including the media and those of us in public life,
to give this family the space it needs to heal its wounds and
strengthen its bonds, to work to lesson the pressure on them as
the matter goes forward in the courts," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"The thing that really matters now is that little boy and his
life and his family, and I think at least for the next several
days the less we all say about it and the more time he has to
breathe the air of a normal life, the better," he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the raid ordered by Reno Saturday, Clinton praised
the attorney general. "They had a very, very difficult job to do
with no easy choices, and I am grateful that they were able to
safely reunite the young boy with his father," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, the U.S. State Department announced that it
will allow four playmates of the Cuban boy, Elian Gonzalez, to
come from Cuba to visit him here for about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular briefing, State Department spokesman
James Rubin said visa requests from the four will be dealt with on
an expedited basis once they are received. One adult will be
permitted to accompany each child.
</P>
<P>
The department issued visas almost three weeks ago to Elian's
former kindergarten teacher, a pediatrician and a male cousin,
Rubin noted.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. federal government seized the six-year-old Cuban boy
from the home of his Miami relatives in a predawn raid Sunday and
reunited Elian and his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, ending a five-
month standoff between the government and Elian's Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
Despite the happy reunion of the father and son, some U.S.
politicians were critical of the administration's handling of the
case.
</P>
<P>
Defending the government's handling of the case soon after the
raid, Clinton and Reno both indicated that the authorities used
force to remove Elian from his relatives in Miami after they
refused to surrender the boy voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
Elian, his step mother, his father and his half brother have
been staying at a residence at nearby Andrews Air Force Base. They
plan to move shortly to the Wye Plantation, located in a secluded
area on Maryland's Eastern Shore, while awaiting court action over
whether Elian should stay in the U.S. or return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued on November 25 near a shipwreck in the
Atlantic sea off Florida after his mother and 10 others drowned
when their boat capsized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
