<HEADLINE> World Bank Provides Emergency Aid to Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved
Tuesday a credit of 35 million U.S. dollars to help Burundi
stabilize its economy.
</P>
<P>
The Emergency Economic Recovery Project will assist the
government in preparing an environment for economic recovery and
restore essential social services to facilitate and support the
ongoing negotiations for peace and reconciliation, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The credit will also support the recovery of the private sector;
finance public expenditures for rehabilitation in health,
education, and agricultural infrastructure; and improve economic
productivity for households affected by the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Since Burundi's internal conflict, progress has been made in
political reconciliation and in establishing security, the bank
said. Social indicators have, however, deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
In light of the ongoing peace process, the worsening poverty
and the emergency, an Interim Strategy Report was prepared by the
World Bank to guide donor assistance over the next 24 months.
</P>
<P>
This strategy proposes a framework for donors to address rising
poverty, taking into consideration the underlying factors and
causes of conflict in Burundi and the triggers leading to repeated
violence. The Emergency Economic Recovery Project is par of the
Interim Strategy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
